1775441095741781	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyuAo		item.create	bn-n1zk	{"description":"## Bug\n\nAfter `maw ws merge`, LFS-tracked files appear as raw binary blobs in the merged commit instead of pointer blobs. `git lfs fsck --pointers` flags them as \"should have been a pointer but was not\".\n\n## Root cause (two interacting issues)\n\n### 1. `collect_snapshots` reads smudged working-tree files, not committed blobs\n\n`src/merge/collect.rs:203` (`read_workspace_file(&ws_path, path, ws_id)`) reads file bytes from the **working tree**. After the LFS smudge post-pass, the working tree has real binary content (100 KB+). But the workspace's COMMITTED blob (written by `git add` which ran git-lfs clean) is a pointer (~130 bytes).\n\nSo the merge sees 100 KB of raw binary and feeds that to `write_blob_at` / `build_merge_commit`.\n\n### 2. `write_blob_with_path` is a no-op on bare repos\n\n`crates/maw-git/src/lfs_clean.rs` falls through to plain `write_blob` when `repo.workdir()` is None. maw's merge runs on the bare repo root (no workdir), so the LFS clean filter is bypassed entirely.\n\n## Reproduction\n\n1. Create a git repo with `*.bin filter=lfs` and a 100KB binary committed via git-lfs\n2. `maw init` + `maw ws create a --from main`\n3. Replace hero.bin with new 200KB random content in ws/a/\n4. `maw exec a -- git add -A && maw exec a -- git commit -m change`\n5. `maw ws merge a --into default --destroy --message \"merge\"`\n6. `git cat-file -p HEAD:hero.bin | head -c 50` shows raw binary, not pointer\n7. `git lfs fsck --pointers` reports \"should have been a pointer but was not\"\n\n## Fix approaches\n\n### Fix A (prefer): read committed blobs in collect phase\n\nIn `collect_one()`, for Modified/Added paths where the file exists in the workspace HEAD commit, read the committed blob via gix blob read instead of the working-tree file. This gets the correctly-cleaned pointer bytes.\n\n### Fix B: make write_blob_with_path work on bare repos\n\nLoad `.gitattributes` from the merge's target tree (or from `ws/default/.gitattributes`) instead of requiring a workdir. Use `AttrsMatcher::from_entries(...)` with `.gitattributes` blob read from the tree.\n\n### Recommended: both\n\nFix A prevents raw binaries from entering the merge pipeline. Fix B ensures the clean filter is a safety net even when the content is unexpectedly raw.","kind":"bug","labels":["lfs","merge","critical"],"size":"m","title":"maw ws merge writes raw binaries instead of LFS pointers"}	blake3:QQSACRhVFqsFLnQpJodxo9lOHpaj5lSbMC5FzPzvjUs
1775441205105571	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyuQo		item.create	bn-1n97	{"description":"## Bug\n\n`maw ws create` fails entirely when LFS objects are missing from the local store, because `git worktree add` (used internally) invokes git-lfs's smudge filter which hard-fails on missing objects.\n\nmaw's native smudge post-pass gracefully handles missing objects (leaves pointer on disk, warns). But it never gets a chance to run because `git worktree add` fails first.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\n`maw ws create` should succeed and leave pointer stubs on disk (with a warning) when LFS objects are missing. The user can then `git lfs pull` to fetch them.\n\n## Root cause\n\n`crates/maw-git/src/worktree_impl.rs` calls `git worktree add` as a subprocess. This triggers git's built-in checkout, which invokes the `filter.lfs.process` smudge driver. When git-lfs can't find the object locally and can't reach the remote, it fails — and git propagates the failure.\n\nMeanwhile, maw's gix-based `checkout_tree` (which has `opts.filters.drivers.clear()`) is only used for subsequent operations (sync, advance, merge), not for the initial worktree creation.\n\n## Fix\n\nSet `GIT_LFS_SKIP_SMUDGE=1` on the `git worktree add` subprocess call. This tells git-lfs to skip smudging during the initial checkout. Then run maw's native smudge post-pass (which gracefully handles missing objects) immediately after the worktree is created.\n\nAlternative: switch `worktree_add` to use gix-based worktree creation instead of the git CLI subprocess.\n\n## Reproduction\n\n1. Create a git repo with `*.bin filter=lfs` and a binary committed via git-lfs\n2. Delete all files under `.git/lfs/objects/` (or `repo.git/lfs/objects/`)\n3. `maw init` (if not already a maw project)\n4. `maw ws create test --from main` -> ERROR: \"checkout failed: IO error while writing blob\"","kind":"bug","labels":["lfs","create"],"size":"s","title":"maw ws create fails hard when LFS objects missing from local store"}	blake3:waKfmxmWZK5isQCFXvr0tKHnJ35WVgYir3NVXesqtHk
1775441264324619	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyugo		item.create	bn-mhg0	{"description":"## Bug\n\nAfter maw's smudge post-pass replaces LFS pointers with real content in the working tree, `git status` shows every smudged LFS file as \"modified\". This blocks `maw ws sync` (which requires a clean working tree) and confuses agents/users who see phantom modifications.\n\n## Root cause\n\nmaw's gix-based checkout writes pointer text to disk and records pointer-file stats (size ~130B, mtime T1) in the git index. The smudge post-pass then overwrites these files with real binary content (size 200KB, mtime T2). The index stat cache no longer matches the working-tree files.\n\nNormally, git-lfs's smudge runs DURING checkout and the index is written AFTER the filter, so the stat cache reflects the smudged content. But maw's post-pass runs AFTER gix has already written the index.\n\nAdditionally, we clear gix's external filter drivers (`opts.filters.drivers.clear()`), which means the index entries don't carry the filter attribute metadata that tells git \"run clean before comparing\".\n\n## Impact\n\n- `git status` in any LFS workspace shows phantom `M` for every LFS-tracked file\n- `maw ws sync` refuses to run (\"uncommitted changes would be lost\")\n- `maw ws merge` may pick up phantom diffs\n- Agents see confusing \"modified\" files they didn't touch\n\n## Fix approaches\n\n### A. Update index after smudge (simplest)\n\nAfter the smudge post-pass, run `git update-index --refresh` in the worktree. This forces git to re-stat every file and update the stat cache. Since git-lfs's clean filter is still configured (in git config), git will realize the working-tree content round-trips through clean to the same pointer blob in the index.\n\n### B. Don't smudge during gix checkout; smudge after git operations\n\nInstead of smudging in `checkout_tree`, do it as a separate step AFTER the workspace is fully set up (including index). Then run `git update-index --refresh` to reconcile.\n\n### C. Write index entries with correct stats\n\nAfter overwriting each pointer file with real content, also update the corresponding index entry's stat (size, mtime, ctime) to match the new file. This requires writing a modified index back. Possible via `gix::index::File` manipulation.\n\n## Reproduction\n\n1. Create a repo with `*.bin filter=lfs`, commit a binary via git-lfs\n2. `maw init && maw ws create test --from main`\n3. `maw exec test -- git status` -> shows `M hero.bin` (phantom modification)\n4. `maw ws sync test` -> fails: \"uncommitted changes would be lost\"","kind":"bug","labels":["lfs","status","critical"],"size":"m","title":"LFS smudge post-pass causes phantom git modifications in every workspace"}	blake3:2jBXgC2pDo36qljpggTn3F7CEEw6nbVot7l_66yAQ_k
1775441304322246	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyuwo		item.comment	bn-mhg0	{"body":"Cascading effect: phantom modifications cause false merge conflicts when two workspaces modify DIFFERENT LFS files. Both appear to have changed the same file because the smudge post-pass makes every LFS file look modified. Tested with ws-a (changed hero.bin) and ws-b (changed logo.png) — merge reported conflict on hero.bin between both workspaces."}	blake3:M2v7ZmzI7HOAopeJHimFqiKd_nJ4hBzlbdHU3e6AMIU
1775500993627472	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyvAo		item.move	bn-n1zk	{"state":"done"}	blake3:7LyOmd4Kul5KjJ2QN-HtfPNBjbWgJctm-wg0T4jfjKU
1775500993653005	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyvQo		item.move	bn-mhg0	{"state":"done"}	blake3:ENa6I8RZdVcW5uFUlCS10Jcw5Oe1kDKpbTClDrx3NKo
1775500993675943	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyvgo		item.move	bn-1n97	{"state":"done"}	blake3:KAQJFBHr8bRH2f2u6jB8Lk6_jmaFEsOzu63Le-4HNfs
1775565435222286	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyvwo		item.create	bn-3q9i	{"description":"## Bug\n\n`write_blob_with_path` loads `.gitattributes` from the workdir first. In maw's bare-repo layout, gix reports the project root as the \"workdir\", but source files (including `.gitattributes`) live under `ws/default/`. The workdir walker finds `ws/default/.gitattributes` but assigns it a `ws/default/` directory prefix, so patterns like `assets/**/*.bin` only match paths prefixed with `ws/default/assets/...` — never the repo-relative `assets/...` paths used by the merge engine.\n\nResult: the LFS clean filter silently fails to match ANY path during merge, and raw binary blobs land in the git tree.\n\n## Fix\n\nAlways read `.gitattributes` from the HEAD tree first (via `load_attrs_from_head`), which gives correct repo-relative paths. Fall back to workdir only when HEAD doesn't exist.\n\nAlso added `AttrsMatcher::is_empty()` to support the fallback logic.","kind":"bug","labels":["lfs","clean","critical"],"size":"s","title":"write_blob_with_path loads attrs from wrong workdir in bare-repo layout"}	blake3:rLUzfibJbdbFprdfHIHui6DgeiIlfe-y1Eb8GtTc7uo
1775565596540757	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEywAo		item.create	bn-1x0i	{"description":"## Bug\n\nThe smudge post-pass runs `git add .` to refresh the index stat cache, but this also stages any UNTRACKED files in the workspace (e.g., `.env`, credentials, temp files). If an agent subsequently runs `git commit -A`, those files get committed.\n\n## Fix\n\nChanged `git add .` to `git add -u .` in both `checkout_impl.rs` and `worktree_impl.rs`. The `-u` flag only updates tracked files (running the clean filter for stat refresh) without adding untracked files.","kind":"bug","labels":["lfs","security"],"size":"xs","title":"git add . after smudge accidentally stages untracked files"}	blake3:EGMKn73nV6iSTs58_i-eEk5abGk0lkpYSmAxHuMOnNo
1775565982597341	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEywQo		item.move	bn-3q9i	{"state":"done"}	blake3:Oyk1FWRAg4eGomObfWT6E0eRFNUCPDsSTjfIJAXCdp4
1775565982620995	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEywgo		item.move	bn-1x0i	{"state":"done"}	blake3:dq0qtzr9NA5MpD__oSgrVxDoWVVYxpRy4XKA-mBFXMo
1775570868447332	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEywwo		item.create	bn-2op4	{"description":"## Bug (two related issues)\n\n### 1. Empty file creates non-canonical LFS pointer\nmaw's clean filter creates a pointer for 0-byte files. git-lfs doesn't — it stores empty files as empty git blobs. `git lfs fsck --pointers` reports \"nonCanonicalPointer\" for these.\n\n### 2. Empty LFS pointer causes workspace recovery failure\nAfter `maw ws create`, the checkout writes a 126-byte pointer for `empty.dat`. The smudge post-pass replaces it with 0 bytes (the real content of the empty file). The index stat is updated to size=0. But when `maw ws recover` later tries `git checkout --detach <commit>`, git sees the working tree (0 bytes) differs from the index blob (126-byte pointer) and refuses: \"Your local changes would be overwritten by checkout\".\n\n### Fix\nSkip the LFS clean filter for 0-byte files — consistent with git-lfs behavior. In `lfs_clean.rs`, add an early return for empty data:\n```rust\nif data.is_empty() {\n    return crate::objects_impl::write_blob(repo, data);\n}\n```\n\nAlso skip 0-byte files in the smudge post-pass (pointer for empty content should never be smudged since it will never exist after the clean fix).","kind":"bug","labels":["lfs"],"size":"xs","title":"Empty LFS files create non-canonical pointers + break ws recover"}	blake3:ckUlHGV1iBa1N4y276-DfnXt1WhLxRgd73zoYAKgfw4
1775571057433449	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxAo		item.create	bn-3qy8	{"description":"## Bug\n\nWhen a workspace modifies `.gitattributes` to REMOVE an LFS pattern and then modifies a file of that type, the merge still applies the LFS clean filter using the OLD `.gitattributes` from HEAD. The file ends up as a pointer even though it should now be stored as raw content.\n\n## Root cause\n\n`write_blob_with_path` in `lfs_clean.rs` calls `load_attrs_from_head(repo)` which reads `.gitattributes` from the repo's HEAD tree. During merge, HEAD is the PREVIOUS epoch — before the workspace's changes land. If the workspace changed `.gitattributes`, the clean filter uses stale rules.\n\n## Example\n\n1. Repo has `assets/**/*.bin filter=lfs` in `.gitattributes`\n2. Workspace removes that pattern from `.gitattributes`\n3. Workspace modifies `assets/sprites/player.bin` — `git add` correctly stores raw binary (new attrs, no LFS)\n4. `maw ws merge` builds the new tree. `write_blob_with_path` reads HEAD's old `.gitattributes`, sees `*.bin` is still LFS, cleans the raw binary to a pointer\n5. Merged commit has a pointer for `player.bin` despite the pattern being removed\n\n## Fix\n\nWhen building the merge tree, if `.gitattributes` is among the resolved changes, use the NEW `.gitattributes` content for the clean filter instead of HEAD's.\n\nApproach: in `build_merge_commit`, scan the resolved changes for `.gitattributes` modifications. If found, build the attrs matcher from the new content. Pass the matcher into `write_blob_at` calls. Otherwise fall back to HEAD attrs.\n\nThis is also the correct behavior for the inverse case (ADDING a new LFS pattern in the same merge).","kind":"bug","labels":["lfs","merge"],"size":"m","title":"LFS clean filter uses stale .gitattributes from HEAD during merge"}	blake3:ZRXATFZjJuwDhFD9Yjg0Okg6Uq_cQZ39ohVamTFZetM
1775581003314560	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxQo		item.move	bn-3qy8	{"state":"done"}	blake3:Lb6ioW2o_UTlKsh3HBxCI8ZrRLAlTru8mvwqsc3hjvI
1775581003337746	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxgo		item.move	bn-2op4	{"state":"done"}	blake3:Dq8nZEi3KXMSzMo38g12LN2iYABOcwtaz7nf1cmlPrU
1775582224826249	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxwo		item.create	bn-aqc6	{"description":"## Bug\n\n`maw ws merge` fails when a workspace contains files with non-ASCII characters in their names (e.g., `données.bin`). The error is \"No such file or directory\" because git's porcelain output escapes non-ASCII bytes (e.g., `\"donn\\303\\251es.bin\"` with surrounding quotes and octal escapes), and the collect phase tries to read the escaped path literally.\n\n## Root cause\n\nThe snapshot/diff parser reads `git diff --name-status` or `git status --porcelain` output, which escapes non-ASCII filenames by default. The parser doesn't un-escape these paths before using them as filesystem paths.\n\n## Not LFS-specific\n\nThis is a general path-handling bug in the collect/diff phase, not specific to LFS. It would affect any non-ASCII filename regardless of LFS tracking.\n\n## Fix\n\nEither set `core.quotePath=false` on the git subprocess calls (disables escaping), or parse and un-escape the quoted paths in the diff/status output parser.","kind":"bug","labels":["merge","path-handling"],"size":"m","title":"Non-ASCII filenames break collect phase (git path escaping)"}	blake3:1dPC8UmECsYDU2OHZ75-k7yfjmwJ2O46ceVSTreGQWA
1775582525322559	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyyAo		item.create	bn-5kad	{"description":"## Goal\n\nAudit and eliminate all remaining `Command::new(\"git\")` subprocess calls across maw. The gix migration was declared complete but 371 git CLI calls remain across 30+ files. These cause:\n\n- Performance overhead (subprocess spawn per call)\n- Path escaping bugs (e.g., non-ASCII filenames in git diff/status output)\n- Hard dependency on git binary availability and version\n\n## Current state (371 calls by module)\n\n| Calls | File | Area |\n|---|---|---|\n| 55 | maw-cli/v2_init.rs | Project initialization |\n| 38 | maw-cli/workspace/working_copy.rs | Checkout, stash, conflict detection |\n| 35 | maw-core/backend/git.rs | Git backend for workspace operations |\n| 21 | maw-cli/workspace/recover.rs | Workspace recovery |\n| 19 | maw-cli/workspace/capture.rs | Snapshot capture |\n| 17 | merge/collect.rs | Merge collect phase (diff + hash-object) |\n| 17 | maw-cli/transport.rs | Remote transport |\n| 15 | maw-cli/workspace/sync.rs | Workspace sync |\n| 15 | maw-cli/changes/mod.rs | Change tracking |\n| 13 | maw-core/oplog/write.rs | Operation log writes |\n| 12 | maw-cli/epoch_gc.rs | Epoch garbage collection |\n| 11 | maw-core/refs.rs | Ref manipulation |\n| 11 | maw-cli/push.rs | Push to remote |\n| 10 | maw-git/stash_impl.rs | Stash operations |\n| 9 | maw-core/merge/build.rs | Merge tree building |\n| 9 | maw-cli/workspace/merge.rs | Merge orchestration |\n| + ~80 more across remaining files | | |\n\n## Known permanent carveouts\n\n- push/fetch (gix-protocol too low-level for reliable remote ops)\n\n## Priority\n\nThe collect phase (merge/collect.rs) and working_copy.rs are highest priority — they're in the hot path for every merge and directly caused the unicode filename bug.","kind":"goal","labels":["gix","performance"],"size":"xl","title":"Audit + eliminate remaining 371 git CLI subprocess calls"}	blake3:tjLHfEjhyAbTdAjsKk4jfLQdsE-qZ7i_A8lM2CaLwGM
1775582766027783	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyyQo		item.move	bn-aqc6	{"state":"done"}	blake3:TOSIsTJ9DMHxm-C5CaNPOnMs4937Vdw6jNmtG0iRNPw
1775760875248260	ward-dev	itc:v3:AWLk-eSZPknJ0AAAAAAAQevvVr6uuAAAAAEtAg		item.create	bn-18dj	{"description":"When a workspace is 'stale' (behind current epoch) AND has local commits ahead of its original base, `maw ws sync --rebase` drops the local commits instead of rebasing them onto the new epoch.\n\nRepro:\n1. Create workspace from epoch A\n2. Make commits in workspace (now at A + local commits)\n3. Another workspace merges, advancing epoch to B\n4. `maw ws sync <ws> --rebase` — says 'no commits ahead of epoch' and fast-forwards to B\n5. Local commits are LOST — not rebased onto B\n\nExpected: sync --rebase should detect the local commits (between original base A and workspace HEAD), then rebase them onto epoch B.\n\nActual: sync sees the workspace is behind epoch B and does a fast-forward, discarding any local commits that were based on A.\n\nImpact: Lost 25 Java CVE manifest entries (50 lines) that an agent had committed. Recovery snapshot captured 'none' because at destruction time the workspace appeared to have 0 commits ahead.\n\nThis is a data loss bug — maw's core invariant is 'no work is ever lost'.","kind":"task","labels":["bug"],"title":"Bug: ws sync --rebase drops commits on stale workspace instead of rebasing"}	blake3:akG-s4YIkVH-cDnzW6NIdwqExyaJSHLQozZ26T4uVbQ
1775761521241745	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErAQ		item.create	bn-nvh6	{"description":"## Bug\n\nWhen an LFS-tracked file's pointer references an oid that doesn't exist in the local store, the file silently disappears from the working tree after merge. No file, no error, no warning — git status is clean. The file IS in the committed tree (pointer blob exists) but the working tree has nothing.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nThe file should appear on disk as the raw pointer text (~130 bytes), with a warning logged that the LFS object is missing. This is what `checkout_tree` does for normal checkouts (the smudge post-pass logs a warning and leaves the pointer). But the default workspace update after merge uses a different code path that loses the file.\n\n## Reproduction\n\n1. Create a workspace, add a file whose content is crafted pointer text with a fake oid\n2. git add + commit (git-lfs passes pointer text through as-is)\n3. maw ws merge → file is in the committed tree but missing from ws/default/\n\nThis also affects normal LFS files when the local store doesn't have the object (e.g., after git clone without git lfs pull).\n\n## Likely root cause\n\nThe default workspace update after merge goes through `update_default_workspace` in merge.rs, which likely uses `git checkout` (CLI) or a different path than `checkout_tree`. If git-lfs's smudge filter fails (object not in store, no remote configured), the file may not be written to disk, and our smudge post-pass never sees it.","kind":"bug","labels":["lfs","merge","data-loss"],"size":"m","title":"LFS file with missing object silently disappears from working tree after merge"}	blake3:oRDchL5QO_-IbK7YePmXiA7mJmffo3sSDb2FWWZBg2U
1775764551813080	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErAg		item.move	bn-nvh6	{"state":"done"}	blake3:7OmqPy3qT-UpO18aQQNUgGvlcc-BxzWn6vpcJJ4LcSA
1775766007759774	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz9AE		item.update	bn-5kad	{"field":"title","value":"Audit + eliminate remaining 371 git CLI subprocess calls"}	blake3:b99QivOXGuZjT55h5_-bTwgW5cBEK0iEdm4ULGIL0u4
1775766007772018	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz9QE		item.update	bn-5kad	{"field":"description","value":"## Goal\n\nAudit and eliminate all remaining `Command::new(\"git\")` subprocess calls across maw. The gix migration was declared complete but 371 git CLI calls remain across 30+ files. These cause:\n\n- Performance overhead (subprocess spawn per call)\n- Path escaping bugs (e.g., non-ASCII filenames in git diff/status output)\n- Hard dependency on git binary availability and version\n\n## Current state (371 calls by module)\n\n| Calls | File | Area |\n|---|---|---|\n| 55 | maw-cli/v2_init.rs | Project initialization |\n| 38 | maw-cli/workspace/working_copy.rs | Checkout, stash, conflict detection |\n| 35 | maw-core/backend/git.rs | Git backend for workspace operations |\n| 21 | maw-cli/workspace/recover.rs | Workspace recovery |\n| 19 | maw-cli/workspace/capture.rs | Snapshot capture |\n| 17 | merge/collect.rs | Merge collect phase (diff + hash-object) |\n| 17 | maw-cli/transport.rs | Remote transport |\n| 15 | maw-cli/workspace/sync.rs | Workspace sync |\n| 15 | maw-cli/changes/mod.rs | Change tracking |\n| 13 | maw-core/oplog/write.rs | Operation log writes |\n| 12 | maw-cli/epoch_gc.rs | Epoch garbage collection |\n| 11 | maw-core/refs.rs | Ref manipulation |\n| 11 | maw-cli/push.rs | Push to remote |\n| 10 | maw-git/stash_impl.rs | Stash operations |\n| 9 | maw-core/merge/build.rs | Merge tree building |\n| 9 | maw-cli/workspace/merge.rs | Merge orchestration |\n| + ~80 more across remaining files | | |\n\n## Known permanent carveouts\n\n- push/fetch (gix-protocol too low-level for reliable remote ops)\n\n## Priority\n\nThe collect phase (merge/collect.rs) and working_copy.rs are highest priority — they're in the hot path for every merge and directly caused the unicode filename bug."}	blake3:Lu0lKrwYQ9FEOlm69LVJkv-CtvqF4LDavBGOPL26ci8
1775766007780441	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz9gE		item.update	bn-5kad	{"field":"kind","value":"goal"}	blake3:WCOGTAfZjTYSeaeTZockcIAYlwXRtVNI61WF8GFypTI
1775766007788984	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz9wE		item.update	bn-5kad	{"field":"size","value":"xl"}	blake3:_FZQKqrBUoaUbuu5q1cZl5S7hD-g7AWfJaLC7Ilg4Eo
1775766007797840	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz-AE		item.update	bn-5kad	{"field":"urgency","value":"punt"}	blake3:Zs5yH15HcMas6CdRd5cPzCsds9xXdk_jMC0jPvz207M
1775766007806544	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz-QE		item.update	bn-5kad	{"field":"labels","value":["gix","performance"]}	blake3:lfKW2UKoMIRoV9ixWOTDMJo6WWQEY2b-I923GVeAB4M
1775768713244875	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz-gE		item.update	bn-18dj	{"field":"title","value":"Bug: ws sync --rebase drops commits on stale workspace instead of rebasing"}	blake3:GYY5EIdk8cY_YJhYcUtT8nIMqtaQgK4Cp8XV1UH-IC0
1775768713263367	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz-wE		item.update	bn-18dj	{"field":"description","value":"When a workspace is 'stale' (behind current epoch) AND has local commits ahead of its original base, `maw ws sync --rebase` drops the local commits instead of rebasing them onto the new epoch.\n\nRepro:\n1. Create workspace from epoch A\n2. Make commits in workspace (now at A + local commits)\n3. Another workspace merges, advancing epoch to B\n4. `maw ws sync <ws> --rebase` — says 'no commits ahead of epoch' and fast-forwards to B\n5. Local commits are LOST — not rebased onto B\n\nExpected: sync --rebase should detect the local commits (between original base A and workspace HEAD), then rebase them onto epoch B.\n\nActual: sync sees the workspace is behind epoch B and does a fast-forward, discarding any local commits that were based on A.\n\nImpact: Lost 25 Java CVE manifest entries (50 lines) that an agent had committed. Recovery snapshot captured 'none' because at destruction time the workspace appeared to have 0 commits ahead.\n\nThis is a data loss bug — maw's core invariant is 'no work is ever lost'."}	blake3:0zsTfpnuJIivLwNJMjbfIks9Y8d9u0xVklADpiRyhCs
1775768713271942	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz_AE		item.update	bn-18dj	{"field":"kind","value":"task"}	blake3:vwSoEon-m0r7_zNo7F52nzszZkzb3BMAX4fLsNuaw50
