1775782634699378	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErBg		item.create	bn-3oh1	{"description":"The formal model (Stateright) and oracle (G1-G6) only instrument merge operations. The core invariant — \"no committed work is ever lost\" — is not checked after sync, auto-sync, or rebase operations. bn-18dj (data loss in ws sync --rebase) escaped all simulation and formal verification because sync isn't modeled.\n\n## What needs to happen\n\n### 1. Add sync actions to the Stateright model (`crates/maw-assurance/src/model.rs`)\n- New actions in the Action enum: `SyncFastForward`, `SyncRebase`, `AutoSync`\n- Model the decision gate: stale workspace + commits ahead → rebase vs refuse vs fast-forward\n- Model epoch advancing between workspace creation and sync (interleaving with merge actions)\n\n### 2. Extend oracle invariants (`crates/maw-assurance/src/oracle.rs`)\n- G1 (committed no-loss) should be checked after sync operations, not just merges\n- New invariant: every commit reachable from workspace HEAD before sync must be either reachable after sync or explicitly rebased onto the new epoch\n- Check that `committed_ahead_of_epoch` is called with base_epoch, not current_epoch (the actual bn-18dj bug class)\n\n### 3. Add sync to DST harness (`tests/dst_harness.rs`)\n- New CrashPhase variants for sync operations (crash mid-rebase, crash after fast-forward but before epoch ref update)\n- Seeded traces that interleave: workspace creation → local commits → concurrent merges advancing epoch → sync/rebase\n\n### 4. Add sync to workflow DST (`tests/workflow_dst.rs`)\n- New workflow variant: `StaleSyncRebase` — workspace with commits, epoch advances, sync --rebase, verify commits survive\n- Variant with conflicting rebase\n\n## Why\nbn-18dj was a data loss bug that violated the core invariant. It existed in all three sync call sites from the start and was never caught because sync isn't in the model. This is a class of bug, not a one-off — any future change to the sync decision logic could reintroduce it.\n\n## Scope\nThis touches maw-assurance (model, oracle), the DST harness, and workflow DST. It does not require changes to maw-core or maw-cli — it's purely test/verification infrastructure.","kind":"task","title":"Add sync/rebase actions to formal model and oracle invariant checks"}	blake3:cpSumrV_SZXoFSlfcwitNzzbwXaeuqoVT4oDPdTXSpE
1775845048657634	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErBw		item.move	bn-3oh1	{"state":"done"}	blake3:NaNRTO3KvhxHFzhdDJo9RPRRa4rX9X0HJfiUgm6VBj0
1775845056280462	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErCA		item.comment	bn-3oh1	{"body":"Closed: superseded by split into a cheap type-safety fix and a larger formal-model expansion (see replacement bones). Formal model expansion alone is high cost for narrow incremental value once the type fix is in place."}	blake3:6PP3imCP5cji3zBDG3zbWiGcp83j8lp_gBCxGHs2xXo
1775845080562409	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErCQ		item.create	bn-1jso	{"description":"bn-18dj was a wrong-argument bug: committed_ahead_of_epoch was called with current_epoch instead of ws_status.base_epoch at three call sites. Both values are bare String/&str — the type system gave zero help. The same mistake was copy-pasted across all three sites because both values read naturally as \"the epoch\".\n\n## Fix\n\nIntroduce distinct newtypes in maw-core or maw-git:\n\n```rust\npub struct BaseEpoch(GitOid);   // workspace's original epoch (what it was branched from)\npub struct CurrentEpoch(GitOid); // the live epoch ref\n```\n\nFunctions that care about the distinction should take the specific type:\n\n```rust\n// Before: fn committed_ahead_of_epoch(ws: &Path, epoch: &str) -> Option<u64>\n// After:  fn committed_ahead_of_epoch(ws: &Path, base: BaseEpoch) -> Option<u64>\n```\n\nNow passing current_epoch is a compile error.\n\n## Scope\n- Add newtype wrappers with AsRef<str> / Display for ergonomics\n- Update committed_ahead_of_epoch signature\n- Update WorkspaceStatus.base_epoch field type\n- Update all call sites (likely 5-15 sites across sync.rs, merge code, status reporting)\n- Keep String conversion at I/O boundaries (git CLI, ref files) but not in internal APIs\n\n## Why this over formal model expansion\n- Catches the exact bug class mechanically, not probabilistically\n- Cheap (~few hours) vs. days of Stateright work\n- Zero runtime cost\n- Zero model-reality drift risk\n- Future sync.rs changes automatically get the safety check\n\n## Non-goals\n- Not replacing all GitOid usage with newtypes (overkill)\n- Not adding epoch-kind distinctions where the code legitimately doesn't care","kind":"task","title":"Type-safe epoch newtypes to prevent base/current epoch mixups","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:Sz-9QSUlFf_T1rty7r5KyXsZjJ24H_yzMS8dRjMpjGY
1775845094989590	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErCg		item.create	bn-3o7w	{"description":"Add a property-based test that fuzzes the ws sync decision logic to catch any future regression in the base-epoch vs current-epoch comparison class of bug.\n\n## Property\n\nFor any sequence of (workspace_create, local_commit*, concurrent_merge*, sync_operation):\n- If the workspace has N > 0 committed commits ahead of its base epoch, then after sync (without --rebase), the workspace HEAD must be unchanged and all N commits must still be reachable from HEAD.\n- If sync is invoked with --rebase, every commit from base..HEAD_before must be reachable from HEAD_after (possibly with different OIDs due to rebase replay).\n- In no case should committed content disappear from the workspace.\n\n## Scope\n- Add a proptest target in tests/sync_proptest.rs (or integrate into existing proptest files)\n- Generate small random workflows (bounded at ~4 commits, ~3 epoch advances)\n- Use the existing TestRepo harness\n- Target: 100-256 cases per test run\n\n## Why this in addition to the newtype fix (bn-1jso)\n- Newtypes catch the specific \"wrong variable\" mistake at compile time\n- Proptest catches logic errors that newtypes can't (e.g., a future refactor that computes the \"base\" dynamically and gets the formula wrong)\n- Cheap to maintain — doesn't require modeling sync in Stateright\n- Runs in the existing cargo test workflow, not a separate harness\n\n## Non-goals\n- Not modeling sync in the Stateright formal model (that's a separate, much larger effort)\n- Not crash injection — the DST harness is the right place for that","kind":"task","title":"Proptest for ws sync decision gate"}	blake3:YWMJBNh_3iCMCRPvkZ0v09StyqWE_FRPJJr6wlj9Yuc
1775845111903422	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErCw		item.create	bn-1ww6	{"description":"Long-horizon project: extend the maw-assurance formal model to cover sync and rebase operations, not just the merge protocol.\n\n## Why deferred\nThe cheap, high-value fixes for the bn-18dj bug class are:\n1. Newtype wrappers to prevent argument mixups at compile time (bn-1jso)\n2. Proptest for the sync decision gate (bn-3o7w)\n3. The 5 regression tests already in tests/sync.rs\n\nThe formal model expansion is the principled answer but has significant costs:\n- Stateright state-space explosion when sync is interleaved with concurrent merges\n- Model-reality drift: keeping the model in sync with sync.rs changes is ongoing tax\n- DST runtime cost roughly doubles\n- Multi-day effort requiring deep Stateright familiarity\n\nThe value is catching *future classes* of sync bugs that the type system and proptests can't reach — e.g., ordering bugs in crash recovery mid-rebase.\n\n## Scope (when we do this)\n1. Add Action variants: SyncFastForward, SyncRebase, AutoSync\n2. Add oracle invariant G7: committed no-loss across sync operations\n3. Add CrashPhase variants for sync operations in DST harness\n4. Add StaleSyncRebase workflow to workflow_dst.rs\n5. Tune state-space exploration bounds to keep CI time reasonable\n\n## Prerequisites\n- bn-1jso (newtype safety) should land first — reduces the action space the model needs to explore\n- Should revisit after any sync.rs refactors so we're modeling stable APIs\n\n## When to do this\n- After 2-3 more sync-related bugs that the type system + proptest missed\n- Or as part of a broader assurance investment push\n- Not before we've exhausted the cheaper options","kind":"task","title":"Add sync/rebase actions to Stateright formal model (deferred)","urgency":"punt"}	blake3:QrzXSlheY5GvmUXyj7KGLZL9-8QKqt17-pOVrA6JZYo
1775942577655649	ward-dev	itc:v3:AWLk-eSZPknJ0AAAAAAAQevvVr6uuAAAAAEtAw		item.create	bn-3h90	{"description":"## Summary\n\nHit two related `ws merge` bugs during a ward session where five ephemeral\nworkspaces (`bn-1ep9`, `bn-n4va`, `bn-2vyt`, `bn-3f9r`, `bn-202c`) each\nappended Java CVE entries to a single shared manifest.toml. Every workspace\nhit the same sequence on merge and required the same ugly workaround. The\nsecond workspace's workaround then corrupted maw's op-log checkpoint for\n`default`, producing a persistent non-fatal warning on every subsequent merge.\n\nEverything worked in the end (all 5 merged, manifest consistent, git clean),\nbut the workflow was painful and the op-log checkpoint is still stale as of\nthis filing.\n\n## Bug 1: Phantom \"unresolved rebase conflict\" state after a clean resolve\n\n### Repro (observed on workspace `bn-n4va`)\n\n1. `maw ws create --from main bn-n4va` off epoch E0.\n2. Agent commits `feat: +16 entries` appending to `tests/cve-registry/manifest.toml`.\n3. A sibling workspace (`bn-1ep9`) merges cleanly, advancing epoch to E1.\n4. `maw ws merge bn-n4va --into default --destroy ...` → fails with\n   \"Workspace 'bn-n4va' is stale (behind current epoch)\".\n5. `maw ws sync bn-n4va --rebase` → hits a legitimate conflict in\n   `manifest.toml` (both sides appended entries, no actual semantic conflict).\n   Reports: `Rebase complete: 0 commit(s) replayed, 1 with conflicts.`\n6. I strip conflict markers with a Python script that keeps both sides\n   (preserving append order), `git add`, and commit:\n\n       [detached HEAD 655274d1] fix: resolve rebase conflicts (keep both sides)\n\n7. `maw ws conflicts bn-n4va` → `No conflicts found. 1 workspace(s) can be\n   merged cleanly: bn-n4va`\n8. `maw ws resolve bn-n4va --list` → `No conflicted files in 'bn-n4va'.`\n9. `maw ws sync bn-n4va` → `Workspace 'bn-n4va' is up to date.`\n10. `maw ws merge bn-n4va --into default --destroy ...` →\n\n        Adopting workspace: bn-n4va\n\n        Error: Workspace 'bn-n4va' has 1 unresolved rebase conflict(s).\n          Resolve conflicts first, then retry the merge.\n          To see conflicts: maw ws conflicts bn-n4va\n          To force merge anyway: maw ws merge bn-n4va --into default --force (not yet implemented)\n\n`ws conflicts`, `ws resolve --list`, and `ws sync` all agreed the workspace\nwas clean. `ws merge` disagreed. There was no escape hatch — `--force` is\nadvertised in the error text but not implemented.\n\n### What I believe is happening\n\n`maw ws sync --rebase` records \"this workspace has N unresolved conflicts\" in\nsome internal state when the rebase hits a conflict. That counter is not\ndecremented when the user resolves the conflict by committing a regular\n`fix: resolve rebase conflicts` commit on top. The resolution path expected\nis probably `maw ws resolve ... --keep ...` — but that command returned \"No\nconflicted files in 'bn-n4va'\" because by the time I ran it I had already\nstripped markers (conflict was real at `ws sync` time; by `ws resolve` time\nthe working copy was clean).\n\nSo the state tracker and the worktree diverge: worktree is clean, state says\n\"1 unresolved\". No documented command reconciles the two.\n\n### Proposed fixes (any one unblocks me)\n\n1. When `ws merge` adopts a workspace, re-examine the worktree/HEAD and\n   refresh the conflict counter from ground truth instead of trusting stale\n   state.\n2. `maw ws resolve <ws> --clear` (or `--ack-clean`) that force-clears the\n   unresolved-conflicts counter when the worktree actually has no markers.\n3. Teach `ws resolve --keep <side>` to work even when the file is already\n   marker-free (treat \"no markers\" as \"already resolved, just update state\").\n4. Honor the user's commit: if `HEAD` advanced past the commit that\n   introduced the conflict AND the tree has no markers, auto-clear.\n5. Implement the `--force` flag that `ws merge` already advertises in its\n   error message.\n\n## Bug 2: Orphaned op-log blob after `ws destroy --force` + `ws create`\n\n### Repro\n\nContinuing from Bug 1 above:\n\n1. Unable to merge bn-n4va, I fell back to a destroy/recreate workaround:\n   - Copy the resolved `manifest.toml` to `/tmp`.\n   - `maw ws destroy bn-n4va --force` (refused without `--force`:\n     \"has 1 unmerged change(s). Refusing destroy to avoid data loss\").\n   - `maw ws create --from main bn-n4va`.\n   - Copy manifest back, `git add`, commit, `ws merge`.\n2. Same sequence for `bn-3f9r` (also hit Bug 1).\n3. Starting with the `bn-202c` merge (the first merge after the first\n   destroy+recreate cycle), every subsequent merge into `default` printed:\n\n        WARNING: checkpoint write skipped for workspace 'default':\n        checkpoint: op log read error:\n        `git cat-file -p 26e85f43d08b6ae15315821e518ea9b4ff3cee95` failed:\n        not found: blob 26e85f43d08b6ae15315821e518ea9b4ff3cee95:\n        An object with id 26e85f43d08b6ae15315821e518ea9b4ff3cee95\n        could not be found\n\n   The warning persists even after subsequent successful merges and is\n   still present at the time of filing this bone.\n\n### Verification\n\n- `git cat-file -t 26e85f43…` → `fatal: could not get object info` — confirmed missing.\n- `git fsck --no-reflogs` → **zero** missing-object reports. The repo's\n  object graph is 100% clean. Only maw's op log still thinks this blob exists.\n- `grep -r 26e85f43 .manifold/` → no match. The reference lives somewhere I\n  couldn't locate from userspace (packed refs or an unlisted internal ref —\n  `refs/manifold/ws/default` points at a real commit and doesn't mention it).\n- The merges themselves all succeeded. Main advanced, manifest is consistent\n  on disk (2443 entries, `tomllib.load` validates cleanly), the new commits\n  are visible in `git log`.\n\n### Proposed fixes\n\n1. `ws destroy --force` should clean up (or at least invalidate) its\n   workspace's op-log checkpoint state in the parent workspace's view before\n   the backing worktree is removed.\n2. Alternatively, `ws create --from main <name>` with a name that collides\n   with a recently-destroyed workspace should reinitialize the op-log\n   checkpoint from scratch rather than inheriting a dangling reference.\n3. When the checkpoint read fails, maw should treat it as \"cold start\" for\n   that workspace (log once, rebuild the checkpoint on the next successful\n   op) instead of printing the warning on every merge indefinitely.\n4. User-facing recovery command: `maw ws checkpoint --repair <workspace>` or\n   similar, so a user who sees this warning has a documented way out.\n\n## Repro data / artifacts\n\n- Project: `/home/bob/src/ward`\n- Session date: 2026-04-11\n- maw version: v0.58.2 (I believe — `maw --version` not captured during session)\n- Epoch trail from the session:\n  - Started at epoch `b330dc46f43a`.\n  - After bones event log commit + `maw epoch sync`: `9b2c34e9112d`.\n  - After `bn-1ep9` merge: `de849bc5efcb` (clean — Bug 1 triggered on the NEXT merge).\n  - After `bn-n4va` merge (destroy+recreate workaround): `505b437b6390`.\n  - After `bn-2vyt` merge (same workaround): `011bcef9d3b5`.\n  - First occurrence of Bug 2 warning: `bn-202c` merge (advanced to `b7444991…`).\n  - Still warning on `bn-3f9r` merge.\n- Orphaned blob OID: `26e85f43d08b6ae15315821e518ea9b4ff3cee95`.\n- All five workspaces touched only `tests/cve-registry/manifest.toml` (append-\n  to-end edits; no semantic conflicts, just textual overlap because every agent\n  appended to the same region of the same file).\n\n## Why this matters\n\nThis workflow (leader spawns 3-5 ephemeral workspaces, each appends to a\nshared file, leader merges serially) is the intended pattern for parallel\nsubagent dispatch per the ward session playbook. Any merge into a shared file\nhits Bug 1 on the second workspace onward. The destroy/recreate escape hatch\ntriggers Bug 2. So the workflow is currently:\n\n> every parallel dispatch produces N-1 phantom-conflict incidents and\n> permanently corrupts the leader workspace's op-log checkpoint\n\n…which is painful enough that the next reflex is \"just run them sequentially,\"\ndefeating the parallelism.\n\n## Nice-to-have alongside the fix\n\n- Document the intended resolution path for \"conflict introduced by\n  `ws sync --rebase`, user resolved by normal commit on top\" in the error\n  output so users don't have to reverse-engineer it.\n- Make `maw ws conflicts` and `maw ws merge`'s internal conflict check use\n  the same source of truth — right now they demonstrably disagree.","kind":"bug","size":"m","title":"ws merge: phantom rebase conflict + orphaned op-log blob after destroy/recreate workaround"}	blake3:ZZ9YltncSugq6OOxfSrEfjpkqAutnFDiyzPHSQ3TBPs
1775944134308681	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErDA		item.move	bn-3h90	{"state":"done"}	blake3:jQf3R3RYPzqe3FmuNnaBD3YOGALoENWa3mvRUvOG9ZY
1775954746148609	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErDQ		item.create	bn-opm7	{"description":"## Motivation\n\nOver a single week we shipped v0.58.1 → v0.58.4 — four patch releases, each fixing a significant bug discovered by the user's production workflow (ward repo with 5-way parallel workspace dispatch). Retrospective on the fixes:\n\n| Release | Bug class |\n|---------|-----------|\n| v0.58.1 (bn-18dj) | Wrong argument from primitive types: `committed_ahead_of_epoch(current_epoch)` instead of `base_epoch`, copy-pasted to 3 sites |\n| v0.58.2 | Two parallel code paths (BUILD phase + stash replay) had independent, incomplete knowledge of .gitattributes |\n| v0.58.3 Bug 1 (bn-3h90) | Cached `rebase_conflict_count` field drifted from worktree ground truth |\n| v0.58.3 Bug 2 (bn-3h90) | `ws destroy` cleaned up 2 of 3 owned refs — the third was forgotten |\n| v0.58.4 (bn-3h90 follow-up) | `find_conflicted_files` 256KB read limit silently missed large files; `ws conflicts` trusted merge engine over ground truth and lied when only one workspace had embedded markers |\n\n**Three structural patterns repeat across all of these:**\n\n1. **Primitive-typed API boundaries.** `&str` for epochs, ref names, paths — the compiler can't distinguish `base_epoch` from `current_epoch`, or `repo_root` from `workspace_path`. Copy-paste spreads mistakes to N sites.\n2. **Cached state that should have been derived.** Counters and flags stored in TOML when the ground truth is git or the worktree. Caches drift; derivations can't.\n3. **Workspace lifecycle is implicit.** A workspace \"owns\" N refs + M metadata files + a worktree + an oplog chain + recovery data. There's no single place that enumerates what a workspace consists of, so cleanup operations miss bits.\n\n**And the testing gap:** our current suite is shaped like a happy-path sieve — it verifies specific scenarios but doesn't check cross-cutting invariants that should hold after *any* operation. If we'd had an invariant like `worktree_has_markers(ws) ↔ counter > 0 ↔ ws_conflicts_reports_unclean(ws)`, the entire bn-3h90 class (3 shipped fixes) would have been caught the first time, not the fourth.\n\n## Goal\n\nEliminate the three bug classes above via:\n- **Targeted refactoring** that prevents the bugs from being written in the first place (newtypes, centralized ownership sets, no drift-prone caches).\n- **Property-based lifecycle invariant tests** that fail loudly when any operation leaves state inconsistent.\n- **Parser fuzzing** for the small number of text parsers that have a history of edge cases.\n\n## Non-goals\n\n- **Rewriting maw.** This is surgical, not a ground-up redesign. Most of maw is fine; the hot spots are concentrated in 3-4 files.\n- **Full Stateright model expansion** (bn-1ww6). That's the principled answer but expensive. Proptest invariants cover ~80% of the value at ~20% of the cost. Revisit after the harness lands and matures.\n\n## Related bones\n- bn-1jso (urgent) — type-safe epoch newtypes\n- bn-3o7w — proptest for ws sync decision gate\n- bn-1ww6 (punt) — Stateright lifecycle expansion (deferred until proptest is exhausted)\n\n## Success criteria\n- Bug rate drops meaningfully (no week with 4 patch releases).\n- New features are forced through the invariant harness; regressions caught pre-ship.\n- Workspace lifecycle operations are defined in one place, not scattered.\n- Parsers have fuzz coverage with seed corpora of real-world inputs.","kind":"goal","labels":["refactor","testing"],"title":"Harden maw against drift, cleanup, and primitive-type bug classes","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:m81slUfJnQmxp8eSY5ZrORqGOxAD6YMCLLyAeJZgC3E
1775954781235262	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErDg		item.create	bn-3fy4	{"description":"Build a proptest-based harness that generates random sequences of workspace operations and checks a set of cross-cutting invariants after every applied operation. Part of bn-opm7.\n\n## Why this is the biggest unlock\n\nCurrent tests are \"scenario tests\" — set up state X, run operation Y, assert output Z. They cover happy paths and specific regressions but miss **state consistency across operations**. Every recent bug (bn-18dj, bn-3h90's three subfixes, the destroy-refs bug) would have been caught by a single invariant checked after every op.\n\n## Design\n\n### 1. Operation generator\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, proptest_derive::Arbitrary)]\nenum Op {\n    Create { name: WsName, persistent: bool },\n    CommitFile { ws: WsName, path: PathSmall, content: ContentSmall },\n    DeleteFile { ws: WsName, path: PathSmall },\n    Merge { sources: Vec<WsName>, target: MergeTarget },\n    Destroy { ws: WsName, force: bool },\n    SyncRebase { ws: WsName },\n    ManualResolveViaGit { ws: WsName },  // strip markers + commit\n    AdvanceDefaultEpoch,\n    // ... add as we learn\n}\n```\n\nUse strategies to bias toward realistic sequences (avoid 50 destroys in a row). Shrinking support so failures minimize to the smallest repro.\n\n### 2. Apply+check loop\n\n```rust\nfn run_scenario(ops: Vec<Op>) -> Result<(), Violation> {\n    let repo = TestRepo::new();\n    for op in ops {\n        let before = snapshot_state(&repo);\n        apply_op(&repo, &op)?;\n        let after = snapshot_state(&repo);\n        check_invariants(&repo, &op, &before, &after)?;\n    }\n    Ok(())\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Invariants (start with these 6, add as bugs are found)\n\n**I1: No zombie state after destroy.** After `destroy(ws)`, no refs under `refs/manifold/{ws,epoch,head,oplog}/<ws>` exist (recovery namespace excepted). This would have caught bn-3h90 Bug 2 immediately.\n\n**I2: Counter coherence.** For every workspace, `metadata.rebase_conflict_count == count_conflict_markers_in_worktree(ws)`. This would have caught bn-3h90 Bug 1 AND its follow-up.\n\n**I3: Three-way conflict agreement.** `worktree_has_markers(ws) ↔ (ws_conflicts_reports_unclean(ws) ∨ ws_resolve_list_reports_unclean(ws))`. The drift between these three was the v0.58.4 bug.\n\n**I4: No hidden loss.** The set of blob SHAs reachable from `refs/manifold/head/*` ∪ `refs/manifold/recovery/*` is monotonically non-shrinking across operations, except for explicit delete/destroy (and even then, recovery should capture the content).\n\n**I5: Idempotence.** `destroy(destroy(ws))` is a no-op. `create(ws)` after `destroy(ws)` starts with a fresh oplog chain (no parent references from the destroyed workspace).\n\n**I6: Merge driver honored.** If `.gitattributes` sets `merge=union` for a path and two workspaces append to it, the merge result contains both appends with no diff3 markers. (The v0.58.2 bug class.)\n\n### 4. Seed corpus\n\nSave minimized failing cases from each discovered bug as replay seeds. These become permanent regression tests that also feed back into the proptest pool as known-interesting starting points.\n\n## Scope\n\n- New crate or test module: `tests/lifecycle_properties.rs`\n- Use proptest with ~256 random cases per invariant per run\n- Each scenario bounded at ~8 ops to keep runs fast (<30s total)\n- CI runs the harness on every PR\n- Seed corpus under `tests/lifecycle_seeds/` for committed regressions\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- **Soft dep on bn-1jso** (newtypes): the invariant checkers are easier to write once there are proper types distinguishing epoch kinds and ref kinds, but not strictly required — the harness can work with raw strings and get refactored later.\n- **Depends on**: knowing the full list of refs a workspace owns — which is the output of bn-opm8 (centralize workspace_owned_refs). Start that first or in parallel.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- 6 invariants implemented and passing on a clean main\n- At least 1 historical bug reproducible as a seed corpus entry\n- Runs in under 60s on CI\n- A new feature PR can add a new invariant in <50 LOC\n- Harness documented in `notes/lifecycle-testing.md`\n\n## Why not Stateright?\n\nStateright (bn-1ww6) is the formally-principled answer but has significant costs: multi-day effort, model-reality drift maintenance, state-space explosion when sync is interleaved with concurrent merges. Proptest covers ~80% of the value at ~20% of the cost and fits cleanly into `cargo test`. Revisit Stateright after a quarter of proptest use reveals any gaps.","kind":"task","labels":["testing","refactor"],"title":"Property-based lifecycle invariant harness","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:jt7bfUD-jPzC0Wfd9ZcShhB8lEj6-rxI_-zz8EOFdFM
1775954808256447	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErDw		item.create	bn-3kcp	{"description":"Define the set of refs a workspace owns in a single place in the code, and have all lifecycle operations (destroy, recover, audit, doctor) iterate that set instead of hand-listing refs. Part of bn-opm7.\n\n## Motivating bug\n\nbn-3h90 Bug 2: `ws destroy` in `crates/maw-core/src/backend/git.rs:375-380` was deleting two refs explicitly:\n\n```rust\nlet ws_ref = manifold_refs::workspace_state_ref(name.as_str());\nlet _ = manifold_refs::delete_ref(&self.root, &ws_ref);\n\nlet epoch_ref = manifold_refs::workspace_epoch_ref(name.as_str());\nlet _ = manifold_refs::delete_ref(&self.root, &epoch_ref);\n```\n\nThe third ref — `refs/manifold/head/<name>` (the oplog head) — was **not deleted**. A later `ws create` with the same name inherited the destroyed workspace's oplog chain, breaking every subsequent merge with \"op log read error: not found: blob ...\" warnings.\n\nRoot cause: there's no single place that says \"this is what a workspace consists of at the ref level\". The destroy function hand-lists refs and forgetting one is silent corruption. When a new ref kind is added (as happened for oplog), every code path that deletes workspaces needs a code change.\n\n## Fix\n\n### 1. Central ownership set\n\nIn `crates/maw-core/src/refs.rs` (or a new `workspace_ownership.rs`):\n\n```rust\n/// Every ref name owned by the workspace \\`name\\`, in deterministic order.\n///\n/// Adding a new workspace-scoped ref kind is a one-line change here —\n/// and every lifecycle operation picks it up automatically.\npub fn workspace_owned_refs(name: &str) -> Vec<String> {\n    vec![\n        workspace_state_ref(name),      // refs/manifold/ws/<name>\n        workspace_epoch_ref(name),      // refs/manifold/epoch/ws/<name>\n        workspace_head_ref(name),       // refs/manifold/head/<name>\n        // Future additions go here — automatically covered by destroy,\n        // doctor, audit, and invariant tests.\n    ]\n}\n\n/// Recovery refs are listed separately because they must SURVIVE destroy.\npub fn workspace_recovery_refs_prefix(name: &str) -> String {\n    format!(\"refs/manifold/recovery/{name}/\")\n}\n```\n\n### 2. Rewrite destroy to iterate\n\nIn `backend/git.rs:destroy`:\n\n```rust\nfor ref_name in manifold_refs::workspace_owned_refs(name.as_str()) {\n    let _ = manifold_refs::delete_ref(&self.root, &ref_name);\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Audit callers\n\nFind every place in the code that enumerates workspace refs by hand:\n\n```bash\ngrep -rn 'workspace_state_ref\\|workspace_epoch_ref\\|workspace_head_ref' \\\n  crates/ src/ --include='*.rs' | grep -v 'workspace_owned_refs'\n```\n\nFor each callsite, decide whether it should iterate the ownership set instead. Known candidates:\n- `ws destroy` (primary)\n- `ws recover` (opposite operation — should use the same list)\n- `ws doctor` (audit command)\n- `prune` and cleanup paths\n\n### 4. Invariant to pair with this (in bn-3fy4)\n\nAfter `destroy(ws)`: assert `workspace_owned_refs(ws).all(|r| !exists(r))`. This invariant would have caught bn-3h90 Bug 2 on the first proptest run.\n\n## Scope\n\n- ~30 LOC refactor\n- Update 3-5 callsites to iterate the set\n- Add a unit test that asserts the ownership set has at least 3 entries (prevents someone accidentally emptying it)\n- Invariant check pairs with bn-3fy4\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `workspace_owned_refs()` exists and is the single source of truth\n- `destroy` iterates it instead of hand-listing\n- All other ref-enumerating callsites either iterate it or have a comment explaining why\n- Adding a new ref kind to the list is a one-line change\n\n## Risk\n\nLow — this is a narrow, mechanical refactor. The only subtlety is making sure recovery refs (which must SURVIVE destroy) are kept separate from the owned set.","kind":"task","labels":["refactor"],"title":"Centralize 'refs owned by a workspace' into one list","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:EMbGKsMmzrqsgylbNqt9WF11O8-eVeXZqmjdTW0kTMY
1775954836822183	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErEA		item.create	bn-2r57	{"description":"Audit every `*_count`, `*_status`, and `is_*` field in `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/metadata.rs` (and similar metadata files). For each, decide whether it should be derived from ground truth instead of cached. Delete the cache when derivation is cheap. Part of bn-opm7.\n\n## Motivating bug class\n\nTwo consecutive bugs on the same field (bn-3h90 Bug 1 and its v0.58.4 follow-up) illustrate the cost of keeping a drift-prone cache:\n\n1. `rebase_conflict_count: u32` is written by `ws sync --rebase` when conflicts occur.\n2. Nothing resets it when the user fixes conflicts via plain git (`git add`, `git commit`).\n3. `ws conflicts`, `ws resolve --list`, and `ws sync` all derive conflict status from the worktree (correct).\n4. `ws merge` trusted the cached counter (wrong).\n5. v0.58.3 \"fix\": reconcile the counter before reading it.\n6. v0.58.4 \"fix\": the reconciler's own detector (`file_has_conflict_markers`) had a 256KB read limit and was silently broken for large files.\n\nThe right fix wasn't any of these — it was to delete the counter and always derive it. A counter that only exists to get out of sync with the ground truth is worse than no counter at all, because it adds a third source of truth that tools can disagree with.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### Phase 1: Audit\n\nFor each persisted field, answer three questions:\n\n1. **What is the ground truth?** (git ref, file content, git status output, etc.)\n2. **How expensive is a fresh derivation?** (milliseconds, seconds, or \"would require a full git walk\")\n3. **Is there a complete invalidation path?** (every mutation site clears/updates the cache)\n\nIf (2) is <50ms AND (3) is incomplete, delete the cache.\nIf (2) is >50ms, keep the cache but make derivation THE source of truth and treat the cache as a hint that must be validated on read.\n\n### Phase 2: Candidate list\n\nRun:\n```bash\ngrep -rE 'pub [a-z_]+: (u32|u64|bool|Option<.*>)' crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/metadata.rs\n```\n\nKnown candidates to audit:\n- `rebase_conflict_count: u32` — **DELETE** (derived from worktree scan)\n- Any `is_stale`, `is_dirty`, `has_uncommitted` — **DERIVE** (from git status)\n- `base_epoch: String` — **KEEP** (needs to survive epoch advances; the workspace's ORIGINAL base is not derivable from current state)\n- `change_id: Option<String>` — **KEEP** (declarative user intent, not derivable)\n- `description: Option<String>` — **KEEP** (human-authored)\n\n### Phase 3: Replace usage sites\n\nFor each field being deleted:\n1. Find all readers: `grep -rn 'ws_meta.<field>'`\n2. Replace each read with a call to a derivation function.\n3. Delete the writers.\n4. Delete the field from the struct.\n5. Run the full test suite.\n\n### Phase 4: Invariant\n\nAdd an invariant to bn-3fy4 for each REMAINING cached field: `cached_value(ws, field) == derive_value(ws, field)` after every operation. If a cache must exist, this invariant guarantees it can't silently drift.\n\n## Scope\n\n- 1 file audit (metadata.rs)\n- Delete at minimum `rebase_conflict_count`\n- Update ~5-10 call sites\n- Add invariants to bn-3fy4 for any remaining cached fields\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Soft dep on bn-3fy4 (invariant harness) — the invariants for remaining caches live there.\n- Order of operations: the audit can happen first, then the deletions land piecemeal, then the invariants close the loop.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- Audit doc at `notes/cached-fields-audit.md` listing every field, its derivation, and a keep/delete decision.\n- At least `rebase_conflict_count` deleted.\n- All tests pass.\n- No new regressions in manual ward-repo dogfooding.\n\n## Risk\n\nMedium — deleting a field touches many call sites. Each deletion needs careful test coverage. Do them one at a time, ship between deletions if possible.","kind":"task","labels":["refactor"],"title":"Audit and eliminate drift-prone cached fields in workspace metadata"}	blake3:O0IM2yMEqOScYA7zxQEVUWBqBaAgE-QDojx7slzOh9A
1775954887748044	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErEQ		item.create	bn-19tb	{"description":"Add targeted fuzz harnesses for the text parsers that have bounded inputs and clear contracts. These are the highest-ROI fuzz targets — each has a history of edge cases and a small enough input space to hit interesting states quickly. Part of bn-opm7.\n\n## Targets (in priority order)\n\n### 1. `.gitattributes` parser — `maw_lfs::attrs::AttrsMatcher`\n\n**Why:** We just added merge-driver parsing in v0.58.2. The existing parser is battle-tested for LFS filter detection but the merge path is new code.\n\n**Invariants to assert:**\n- `from_entries(parse(serialize(rules))) == rules` for any valid input (round-trip)\n- `is_lfs` and `merge_driver` return deterministic results for the same input\n- Never panics on any bytes\n- Later-line-wins semantics match git's behavior (check against ground truth via `git check-attr`)\n\n**Corpus seeds:**\n- Real `.gitattributes` files from maw, ward, and any other projects the user has lying around\n- Pathological patterns: deeply nested `**`, unicode, CRLF, bare `merge`, `-merge`, `!merge`\n- Macro declarations (`[attr]name ...`)\n- Quoted patterns with spaces (currently unsupported — should error, not panic)\n\n### 2. Conflict marker parser — `parse_file_conflicts` in `resolve.rs`\n\n**Why:** The structure of `<<<<<<<` / `|||||||` / `=======` / `>>>>>>>` markers is nontrivial. Nested markers (which we've seen in the wild when rebase commits markers and a later rebase sees those markers again) are a known edge case. Already has a test but only covers well-formed input.\n\n**Invariants:**\n- Never panics on any string input\n- For well-formed markers, output preserves left/right content exactly\n- For malformed markers (unpaired `<<<<<<<`, missing `=======`, etc.), output is either an error OR preserves the raw bytes as context (never silently eats data)\n- Nested markers parse as nested (not flattened)\n\n**Corpus seeds:**\n- Output of `git merge-file --diff3` across real file inputs\n- Hand-crafted pathological inputs: markers inside strings, markers in comments, unterminated marker blocks at EOF\n\n### 3. `WorkspaceId::new` validation\n\n**Why:** Tight validation rules (allowed chars, length, forbidden prefixes). A regression here could let through invalid names that break downstream ref handling.\n\n**Invariants:**\n- Valid names never fail\n- Invalid names never succeed\n- Valid names round-trip through `as_str()` losslessly\n- Never panics\n\n**Corpus seeds:**\n- The names currently in use (default, agent-1, bn-*, etc.)\n- Unicode, control chars, path separators, empty string, very long strings\n\n### 4. diff3 atom recovery — `recover_diff3_atoms` and `parse_diff3_atoms`\n\n**Why:** This function runs on `git merge-file`'s output and extracts structured conflict atoms. Its output drives the `--resolve ID=STRATEGY` syntax. Getting this wrong means the resolve command points at phantom conflict regions.\n\n**Invariants:**\n- Atoms extracted from a marker output, re-rendered, produce the original bytes\n- Atom IDs are stable for the same input content (needed for `--resolve cf-xyz=alice` to work across runs)\n\n## Scope\n\n- New crate-level `fuzz/` directory under each target crate (or a single top-level `fuzz/` for the workspace)\n- Use `cargo-fuzz` (libfuzzer) for the parsers — faster feedback than proptest for byte-level inputs\n- Use `proptest` for `WorkspaceId::new` (which has a small domain)\n- Seed corpus committed to `fuzz/corpus/<target>/`\n- CI runs each target for 30 seconds per PR (fast smoke test), nightly for longer (10 min)\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- 4 fuzz targets wired up with cargo-fuzz or proptest\n- Seed corpus with ≥10 real-world inputs per target\n- Each target runs clean for 5 minutes on the initial commit\n- CI integration so regressions are caught pre-merge\n\n## Risk\n\nLow — fuzz targets are isolated from production code paths. Worst case: a fuzz target finds a pre-existing bug that we add to the backlog. Best case (likely): several pre-existing bugs surfaced.","kind":"task","labels":["testing"],"title":"Fuzz the small-input parsers (gitattributes, conflict markers, WorkspaceId, diff3)"}	blake3:tPpbQP0h_oulVUxivjMwVbSSyEGu2lSIeShV7T-MyTI
1775954926695340	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErEg		item.create	bn-23go	{"description":"The three hottest bug-density files in maw are all 1000-4000 LOC. Every recent bug has touched at least one of them, and several bugs arose because the author (me) couldn't hold all the state in mind at once. Split them into focused submodules. Part of bn-opm7.\n\n## Symptom\n\n| File | LOC | Recent bug density |\n|------|-----|-------------------|\n| `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge.rs` | ~4000 | bn-2fk0, bn-3h90 (both bugs), merge-driver fix, bn-18dj fix |\n| `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/working_copy.rs` | ~1000 | bn-2fk0, v0.58.2 merge-driver fix |\n| `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync.rs` | ~1100 | bn-18dj (3 call sites), bn-3h90 (rebase conflict state), bn-3en5 |\n\nWhen I shipped the v0.58.2 merge-driver fix, I had to touch **both** `merge.rs` and `working_copy.rs` because the same logical operation (3-way merge for shared paths) lived in two parallel implementations. Neither file \"owned\" the shared logic.\n\n## Not a cause, but a strong correlate\n\nBig files aren't the bug. They're a symptom of tangled responsibilities. Splitting doesn't fix the bugs, but it:\n\n1. Makes it harder to ship a fix to one merge path and forget the other (they'd share a helper module).\n2. Makes the invariant harness (bn-3fy4) easier to write because the state is in well-defined slices.\n3. Makes review faster — reviewers can mentally model a smaller file.\n4. Surfaces cases where two functions \"should\" share logic but currently don't.\n\n## Proposed splits\n\n### `merge.rs` (4000 LOC)\n\nCurrent responsibilities (all in one file):\n1. `MergeOptions` struct + dispatch (~300 LOC)\n2. Top-level `pub fn merge()` orchestrator (~600 LOC)\n3. Pre-flight checks (conflict counter, embedded markers, change-id validation, stale detection) (~400 LOC)\n4. `show_conflicts` (`ws conflicts` command) (~200 LOC)\n5. `check_merge` (`--check` mode) (~300 LOC)\n6. `plan_merge` (`--plan` mode) (~200 LOC)\n7. JSON output builders (~300 LOC)\n8. Destroy-after-merge logic (~400 LOC)\n9. Force-checkout fallbacks (~300 LOC)\n10. Resolution parsing (`--resolve ID=STRATEGY`) (~500 LOC)\n11. Workspace replay + stash handling (~500 LOC)\n\n**Suggested split:**\n```\ncrates/maw-cli/src/workspace/merge/\n  mod.rs              — top-level entry, MergeOptions, pub fn merge\n  preflight.rs        — all the pre-merge safety checks\n  show.rs             — ws conflicts command\n  check.rs            — --check mode\n  plan.rs             — --plan mode\n  destroy_after.rs    — post-merge cleanup\n  json_output.rs      — structured output builders\n  resolve_specs.rs    — --resolve ID=STRATEGY parsing\n```\n\n### `working_copy.rs` (1000 LOC)\n\nCurrent responsibilities:\n1. `replay_snapshot` — simple case\n2. `replay_snapshot_with_merge_protection` — the complex 3-way merge case\n3. Path overlap detection\n4. `merge_text_three_way` wrapper (duplicated with maw-git's `merge_text`)\n5. Diff3 marker writing\n6. Stash manipulation\n\n**Suggested split:**\n```\ncrates/maw-cli/src/workspace/working_copy/\n  mod.rs           — entry points\n  replay.rs        — simple and merge-protection replays\n  overlap.rs       — path overlap detection\n  stash.rs         — stash apply/snapshot helpers\n```\n\nAlso: the `merge_text_three_way` wrapper should move to `maw-git::merge` and be shared with the BUILD phase, so future fixes to merge semantics only need to touch one file. (This is the biggest architectural win — it would have prevented the v0.58.2 two-path problem.)\n\n### `sync.rs` (1100 LOC)\n\nCurrent responsibilities:\n1. `sync` entry point (~200 LOC)\n2. `rebase_workspace` — cherry-pick replay logic (~400 LOC)\n3. Auto-sync helper (`auto_sync_if_stale`) (~150 LOC)\n4. Rebase conflict metadata I/O (~100 LOC)\n5. Cross-target guard logic (~200 LOC)\n6. Various checks (`committed_ahead_of_epoch`, etc.) (~100 LOC)\n\n**Suggested split:**\n```\ncrates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/\n  mod.rs              — ws sync entry, auto_sync_if_stale\n  rebase.rs           — rebase_workspace and conflict metadata\n  cross_target.rs     — cross-target guard logic\n  checks.rs           — committed_ahead_of_epoch and related\n```\n\n## Scope\n\n- Pure mechanical refactor — no behavior changes\n- Each split is one PR (can be done sequentially across a week)\n- Each PR must pass the full test suite with no diff in test output\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- **Best done AFTER bn-3fy4** (invariant harness) lands — the harness gives a strong safety net for \"no behavior changed\" during the refactor.\n- **Coordinate with bn-1jso** (newtypes) — the newtypes land in the same files; do the newtype refactor first so it doesn't have to repeat across the split modules.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `merge.rs`, `working_copy.rs`, `sync.rs` no longer exist as single files (they become module directories)\n- No file in the split exceeds 800 LOC\n- Shared 3-way merge logic lives in `maw-git::merge`, called by both BUILD phase and working_copy replay\n- Full test suite passes with no flakes\n- A code-reading review confirms the splits are \"intuitive\" — a reader shouldn't need to hunt across multiple files for one logical operation\n\n## Non-scope\n\n- **Don't change semantics.** If a function has a weird quirk, preserve it as-is and file a follow-up bone. This refactor is about organization, not correctness.\n- **Don't rename public functions** beyond moving them to a new module path.\n\n## Risk\n\nMedium — large mechanical refactor touching hot code. Mitigated by (1) doing it after the invariant harness exists, (2) doing it incrementally file-by-file, (3) running the full test suite + manual ward-repo dogfooding between each split.","kind":"task","labels":["refactor"],"title":"Split merge.rs, working_copy.rs, sync.rs into focused submodules"}	blake3:7y6kcnOtOPT6utMdO2WPzSNYfBbyERT3pCuteWJ6bPs
