1776705486525459	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy2go		item.create	bn-3mpx	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/capture.rs:222-234\n\n**Issue**: When `git stash create` returns `None` after the dirty-path check already found uncommitted work, `capture_dirty_worktree` swallows it as `Ok(None)`. Callers interpret `Ok(None)` as \"workspace clean, nothing to preserve\" and proceed with destroy — losing the dirty files.\n\n**Root Cause**: The `None` branch of `match stash_result` in capture.rs:223–234 logs a warning, resets the index, and returns `Ok(None)`. The function contract in its docstring says `Ok(None)` means \"the workspace is clean *and* at the base epoch (nothing to preserve)\" (capture.rs:86-87). That contract is violated here — we had already detected dirty files on line 107, so the `None` case is an unexpected internal inconsistency, not a \"clean\" state. Returning `Ok(None)` makes it indistinguishable from the clean case.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P1 (violates the Prime Invariant in AGENTS.md: \"No committed work can ever be lost\"; uncommitted work is also expected to be captured by `capture_before_destroy`)\n- Scope: all callers of `capture_before_destroy` — `destroy --force` (create.rs:488), `merge --destroy` (merge.rs:4292), and the capture-replay cycle (working_copy.rs:1127)\n- Reproducibility: rare but real. Triggered when `git status` reports dirtiness but `git stash create` produces no stash (e.g. race where another process cleans the index between `list_dirty_paths` and `stash_create`, odd submodule/embedded-repo state, or index-only ghost changes).\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// capture.rs:222-234\nlet stash_git_oid = match stash_result {\n    Some(oid) => oid,\n    None => {\n        // `stash_create` returns None if there's nothing to stash\n        // (shouldn't happen since we checked dirty_paths, but be defensive)\n        let _ = Command::new(\"git\")\n            .args([\"reset\"])\n            .current_dir(ws_path)\n            .output();\n        tracing::warn!(\"stash_create returned None despite dirty paths\");\n        return Ok(None);     // <-- caller treats this as \"clean\"\n    }\n};\n```\n\nDownstream in working_copy.rs:1130-1140 the caller even documents this as a fallback path:\n```rust\nlet capture = match capture_result {\n    Some(c) => c,\n    None => {\n        tracing::warn!(\n            \"capture returned None despite status check showing work; \\\n             falling back to clean checkout\"\n        );\n        git_checkout_force(ws_path, target_ref)?;   // <-- DATA LOSS\n        return Ok(ReplayResult::Clean);\n    }\n};\n```\nThis explicitly overwrites the working tree when capture unexpectedly returned `None`.\n\n**Context**: The destroy/capture path is the last safety net before work is removed. `capture_before_destroy` is the single choke point that every destructive workspace operation relies on. The `Ok(None)` encoding conflates two very different states: \"clean, nothing to do\" and \"we saw dirty files but failed to snapshot them\".\n\n**Related**: The same ambiguity appears in working_copy.rs:1127 where the capture result drives whether any recovery ref is pinned — so failure silently degrades the recovery surface for every subsequent `maw ws recover`.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","data-loss","capture","safety-invariant"],"size":"s","title":"capture_before_destroy silently loses dirty work when stash_create returns None","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:qi0v6PS4WC3MzulTwj9pxG-Cpa8EzA86GG8ChlNFtnE
1776705530948181	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy2wo		item.create	bn-6cs4	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/undo.rs:15-76\n\n**Issue**: `maw ws undo <name>` restores tracked files to the base epoch and deletes untracked `PatchValue::Add` paths with no pre-undo snapshot. Any uncommitted edits, staged changes, or untracked files in the workspace are unrecoverable afterwards — there is no recovery ref, no destroy record, no way back.\n\n**Root Cause**: The command calls `restore_workspace_to_epoch` (line 44) followed by `remove_added_paths` (line 45) without first calling `capture_before_destroy` or `snapshot_working_copy`. The compensation entry at line 64 (`record_compensation_op`) only writes an oplog marker *after* the destructive action — the content it describes is already gone from disk and the git object store.\n\nContrast with `destroy --force` (create.rs:487-492) which calls `capture_before_destroy` first, pinning the state under `refs/manifold/recovery/`. Undo has no equivalent safety net despite being just as destructive from the user's perspective.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P1 (violates the project's Prime Invariant: \"No work is ever lost in maw\"; AGENTS.md scopes this to committed work, but `maw ws undo` is a \"destroy local changes\" command that users reasonably expect to be recoverable like everything else — `maw ws recover` already has the infrastructure)\n- Scope: everyone who runs `maw ws undo`\n- Reproducibility: 100%. Create a workspace, edit files, add untracked files, run `maw ws undo <name>`, try `maw ws recover` → nothing is listed because no snapshot was captured.\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// undo.rs:30-75 (abridged)\nlet patch_set = compute_patchset(&ws_path, &base_epoch)?;\nif patch_set.is_empty() { ... return Ok(()); }\n\nlet added_paths = collect_added_paths(&patch_set);\nrestore_workspace_to_epoch(&ws_path, &base_epoch)?;  // <-- wipes tracked changes\nremove_added_paths(&ws_path, &added_paths)?;         // <-- deletes untracked files\n\n// ... compute_patchset sanity check ...\n\nlet op_oid = record_compensation_op(&root, &ws_id, &base_epoch, patch_set.len())?;\n```\nNo `capture_before_destroy`, no `snapshot_working_copy`, no `refs/manifold/recovery/*` pin.\n\n`restore_workspace_to_epoch` invokes git's restore subcommand against `--source <epoch>` with both index and worktree flags (see undo.rs:91-113), which discards both the index and the worktree for every tracked path. `remove_added_paths` walks every `PatchValue::Add` entry and calls `remove_file` or `remove_dir_all` (undo.rs:116-138) — again with no snapshot.\n\n**Context**: `maw ws undo` is a user-facing command exposed through the CLI (wired up in workspace/mod.rs:1328: `WorkspaceCommands::Undo { name } => undo::undo(&name)`). Agents and humans may invoke it after a misstep expecting the same safety posture that `destroy --force` and `merge --destroy` provide. AGENTS.md tells readers \"Never assume work is gone. Always check `maw ws recover` first.\" — but for undo, `maw ws recover` would yield nothing.\n\n**Related**: The capture infrastructure already exists (`capture_before_destroy`, `snapshot_working_copy`, `write_destroy_record`) — compare create.rs:486-492 and merge.rs:4292 for the pattern that undo is missing.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","data-loss","undo","safety-invariant"],"size":"m","title":"maw ws undo destroys uncommitted and untracked work with no recovery snapshot","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:_Mv5COOwl5EqncZbckPjaiVPw63gFzP-qT56_M6NXIo
1776705557522321	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy3Ao		item.create	bn-gjm8	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:218-267\n\n**Issue**: When a cherry-pick conflicts during `maw ws sync --rebase`, the rebase unconditionally runs `git add --all` on the conflicted worktree (with literal `<<<<<<<`/`|||||||`/`=======`/`>>>>>>>` markers present) and creates a normal commit via `git commit --no-verify --allow-empty`. The workspace's HEAD advances with content that is textually broken, and this broken commit becomes the parent for every subsequent cherry-pick in the loop. If the user later merges this workspace before resolving, the conflict markers get merged into the target epoch as ordinary source bytes.\n\n**Root Cause**: The \"preserve markers in history so the agent can see them\" design bypasses git's own \"cherry-pick left unresolved\" safeguard (which would normally prevent committing while unmerged paths exist). `git add --all` on conflicted files turns each unmerged entry into a stage-0 blob whose contents are the textual markers, and the follow-up commit seals those markers into history. Errors from both commands are discarded with `let _ = ...` (lines 255-258 and 263-266), so partial failures go unreported.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P1 (data integrity — broken content can propagate to main via `maw ws merge`)\n- Scope: every workspace that hits a conflict during sync-rebase and has more than a handful of commits ahead; every consumer that subsequently merges that workspace\n- Reproducibility: 100% when a cherry-pick during rebase conflicts\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:255-266\nlet _ = Command::new(\"git\")\n    .args([\"add\", \"--all\"])\n    .current_dir(ws_path)\n    .output();\nlet msg = format!(\n    \"rebase: conflict replaying {short_sha} ({} file(s))\",\n    conflict_files.len()\n);\nlet _ = Command::new(\"git\")\n    .args([\"commit\", \"--no-verify\", \"--allow-empty\", \"-m\", &msg])\n    .current_dir(ws_path)\n    .output();\n```\n\nSubsequent iterations of the `for (i, commit_sha) in commits.iter().enumerate()` loop at line 152 then run a fresh `git cherry-pick --no-commit commit_sha` on top of this broken commit — the next cherry-pick's 3-way merge now uses conflict-marker-polluted content as its \"ours\" side, which can produce more spurious conflicts or silently resolve differences against corrupt bytes.\n\nAfter the loop, rebase.rs:271-274 writes the workspace epoch ref to `new_epoch` regardless of whether conflicts were recorded, so `maw ws status` and `maw ws list` see the workspace as \"clean and up to date on the new epoch\" even though its HEAD commit is literally a tree of files full of `<<<<<<<` markers.\n\n**Context**: `rebase_workspace` is reachable via `maw ws sync --rebase` (sync/mod.rs) and may be the default strategy for persistent workspaces. The workspace is then a merge-ready candidate from the perspective of `maw ws merge --check`, which only checks `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/rebase-conflicts.json` existence (rebase.rs:54-61) — not the content of HEAD. If that JSON file is missing (e.g. it was never flushed or was deleted) the poisoned workspace will merge cleanly into the target and carry the markers forward.\n\n**Related**: rebase.rs has no integration tests of the actual rebase flow — only a JSON serialization roundtrip at line 450-479. The conflict-marker-commit behavior is untested end-to-end.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","data-integrity","rebase","merge-safety"],"size":"l","title":"sync --rebase commits conflict markers into workspace HEAD, can poison future merges","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:uc7gl1mt1Q4V6m7RnCs4-_XAx79wNuEp34BFxYQ9tVA
1776705583294277	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy3Qo		item.create	bn-2dy4	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/destroy_record.rs:66-67, 113-124 and capture.rs:47-51\n\n**Issue**: Destroy records and recovery refs are keyed on a second-granularity ISO-8601 timestamp. Two destroys of the same workspace within the same wall-clock second produce colliding filenames and colliding git ref names, so the second operation silently overwrites the first destroy record and the first recovery ref — erasing the first snapshot's evidence from `maw ws recover`.\n\n**Root Cause**: `write_destroy_record` computes `destroyed_at = super::now_timestamp_iso8601()` (line 66) and uses `{filename_ts}.json` (line 113) as the artifact filename. `capture::recovery_ref` builds `refs/manifold/recovery/<ws>/<ts>` with the same function (capture.rs:47-51). When two destroys land in the same second (e.g. a rapid `destroy --force` after a `merge --destroy`, or automated pipelines doing repeated recreate+destroy cycles), both operations produce the same `filename_ts`, the same ref name, and the same `.json` path. The file is overwritten by the second call (see the explicit test at line 621-628 that uses `std::thread::sleep(1s)` precisely to dodge this collision).\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P2 (undermines `maw ws recover` audit trail; recovery ref collision means the first recovery commit becomes unreachable and may be GC'd; the most recent destroy appears to be the *only* destroy)\n- Scope: any workflow that destroys the same workspace name more than once per second (automated harness tests, rapid `destroy → create → destroy` loops, concurrent merge+destroy races)\n- Reproducibility: 100% under a fast automated driver; ~intermittent in human-driven workflows\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// destroy_record.rs:66-67\nlet destroyed_at = super::now_timestamp_iso8601();\nlet filename_ts = destroyed_at.replace(':', \"-\");\n// ...\nlet record_filename = format!(\"{filename_ts}.json\");\nlet record_path = destroy_dir.join(&record_filename);\nwrite_json_atomic(&record_path, &record)?;  // <-- clobbers existing file with same name\n```\n\n```rust\n// destroy_record.rs tests line 621-628 — acknowledges the issue\n// Write first destroy record.\nwrite_destroy_record(...).unwrap();\n\n// The timestamp uses second-level granularity, so we must wait at\n// least one second for the filenames to differ.\nstd::thread::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_secs(1));\n\n// Write second destroy record.\nwrite_destroy_record(...).unwrap();\n```\n\nThe recovery ref collision is parallel:\n```rust\n// capture.rs:47-51\npub fn recovery_ref(workspace_name: &str, timestamp: &str) -> String {\n    let safe_ts = timestamp.replace(':', \"-\");\n    format!(\"{RECOVERY_PREFIX}{workspace_name}/{safe_ts}\")\n}\n```\n\n**Context**: `maw ws recover <name>` relies on `list_record_files` returning every destroy record (destroy_record.rs:199-213) to show history. When records collide, older history disappears and a user who destroyed twice in one second cannot tell the two destroys apart — the more recent one looks like the only one that happened. Similarly, `find_dangling_snapshots` in recover.rs:1110+ groups recovery refs by `(workspace, timestamp)`; a collision means the older snapshot ref is overwritten, and its commit object becomes unreferenced.\n\n**Related**: The `latest.json` pointer (line 117-122) also gets clobbered in the same sequence. Consider adding millisecond (or nanosecond) precision to `now_timestamp_iso8601()`, or suffixing with a monotonic counter when collisions are detected.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","data-integrity","destroy-record","recovery"],"size":"s","title":"Second-granularity destroy-record timestamp causes silent record and recovery-ref collision"}	blake3:JZkCzf3q4yEwlfEvflvcNMsYRNXY9bfSY2kc4ggAb0c
1776705608211359	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy3go		item.create	bn-1psp	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/working_copy.rs:709-720\n\n**Issue**: During the merge stash-replay path (used to preserve a target workspace's local edits across a merge), the call to `repo.stash_apply(oid)` is made with `let _ = ...`, discarding any error. If the stash apply fails (conflict-unfriendly edge case, index lock contention, gix error, corrupt stash object), the function silently proceeds to the 3-way merge loop with non-overlapping local edits missing from the working tree. The user's local edits for non-overlapping files are lost.\n\n**Root Cause**: The surrounding comment acknowledges the semantics — \"stash_apply is a naive overwrite, so overlapping files will get the stash version — we fix those up in step 5 with a proper 3-way merge\" — but the code never checks whether the apply actually happened. Non-overlapping paths (the majority of a typical merge) are never touched by step 5, so they rely entirely on step 4 having succeeded. If step 4 silently failed, the merge commits the target's post-checkout tree without any of the user's non-overlapping local edits.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P2 (data loss risk under specific gix/index conditions; silent — no warning, no error)\n- Scope: every `maw ws merge --into <name>` where `<name>` had uncommitted local edits before the merge\n- Reproducibility: requires stash_apply failure conditions (rare in happy path, but the error is swallowed unconditionally so any failure mode manifests the bug)\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// working_copy.rs:709-720\nlet repo = maw_git::GixRepo::open(ws_path)\n    .map_err(|e| anyhow::anyhow!(\"failed to open repo at {}: {e}\", ws_path.display()))?;\nlet oid: maw_git::GitOid = snapshot\n    .oid\n    .parse()\n    .map_err(|e| anyhow::anyhow!(\"invalid snapshot OID '{}': {e}\", snapshot.oid))?;\nlet _ = repo.stash_apply(oid);   // <-- return value discarded\n\n// Unstage everything for a clean working tree view.\nif let Err(e) = repo.unstage_all() {\n    tracing::warn!(\"failed to unstage after stash apply: {e}\");\n}\n```\n\nCompare with the very next call (`repo.unstage_all()`) which does at least emit a `tracing::warn!` on failure — the adjacent code acknowledges that these errors are surfacable. The stash_apply discard is not.\n\n**Context**: The stash being applied is the recovery snapshot captured before the target workspace's HEAD was checked out to the merge commit (step 1 in this function). It contains the user's pre-merge uncommitted edits. The whole function exists to preserve those edits; a silent failure here defeats the purpose.\n\n**Related**: working_copy.rs contains many other `let _ = ...` calls on state-mutating operations (lines 540, 544, 715, 755, 767, 776, 828, 1167, 1180, 1193, 1206, 1213, 1227). A systematic audit of which of these are safe-to-ignore vs. silent-data-loss is warranted. In particular lines 1167/1180/1193/1213/1227 are rollback-from-rollback paths: if the rollback itself fails the workspace is left in an intermediate corrupt state and the caller is told it was \"rolled back\".","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","data-loss","merge","error-handling"],"size":"s","title":"Merge stash_apply error silently discarded — user's non-overlapping local edits can be lost"}	blake3:PWAd3bGik80zZqaS4mKm6Igy4DPdCOFJUBkFuUq0Oyw
1776705633617361	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy3wo		item.create	bn-3pkx	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:270-274 and sync/checks.rs:139-142\n\n**Issue**: After a rebase completes (with or without conflicts), `rebase_workspace` writes the workspace epoch ref to the new epoch using `let _ = manifold_refs::write_ref(root, &epoch_ref, &oid)`. Two problems:\n\n1. The write happens *before* the conflict check — so workspaces that finished with conflicts still have their epoch ref advanced, advertising them as \"synced to new epoch\" even though HEAD points to a commit full of literal conflict markers.\n2. The return value is discarded; if the ref write fails (e.g. ref lock contention, refs directory not writable), the workspace retains its old epoch ref while HEAD has been rewritten, and the workspace is left in a permanently stale state from maw's perspective despite git believing otherwise.\n\nThe same pattern appears at sync/checks.rs:141 inside `sync_worktree_to_epoch`.\n\n**Root Cause**: The epoch ref write is treated as best-effort, but it's the only signal that downstream commands (`maw ws status`, `maw ws list`, `maw ws merge --check`, `maw ws overlap`) use to compute whether a workspace is in sync or has drifted. Silently skipping it or advancing it unconditionally both lead to incorrect status reporting.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P2 (drives wrong decisions in merge/status/overlap logic; compounds with the conflict-marker-commit issue — a workspace that should be blocked from merge can pass `maw ws merge --check` because its epoch ref says it's current)\n- Scope: every `maw ws sync --rebase` with conflicts, every `maw ws sync` that races with another ref writer\n- Reproducibility: 100% for the \"conflict + ref advanced anyway\" case; intermittent for the write-failure case\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:270-274\n// Step 3: Update workspace epoch ref.\nif let Ok(oid) = maw_core::model::types::GitOid::new(new_epoch) {\n    let epoch_ref = manifold_refs::workspace_epoch_ref(ws_name);\n    let _ = manifold_refs::write_ref(root, &epoch_ref, &oid);   // <-- unconditional + ignored\n}\n\n// Step 4: Record conflict metadata and update workspace metadata.\nif !conflicts.is_empty() {\n    // ... write .manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/rebase-conflicts.json ...\n}\n```\n\nThe ordering inverts the expected safety: we first tell maw \"you're up to date\", then record that you aren't.\n\n```rust\n// sync/checks.rs:139-142\nif let Ok(oid) = maw_core::model::types::GitOid::new(epoch_oid) {\n    let epoch_ref = manifold_refs::workspace_epoch_ref(ws_name);\n    let _ = manifold_refs::write_ref(root, &epoch_ref, &oid);\n}\n```\nSame pattern — a silent best-effort write following a successful checkout.\n\n**Context**: `maw ws merge --check` and `maw ws overlap` rely on the workspace epoch ref being an accurate statement of \"the epoch this workspace's HEAD is rebased on\". When the ref lies (advanced past a conflicted rebase, or stuck at the old epoch after a successful sync), merge-ready detection produces the wrong answer — either a conflicted workspace looks mergeable (bad) or a cleanly-synced workspace is flagged as stale (annoying but not dangerous).\n\n**Related**: The same silent-best-effort pattern appears in advance.rs:170 for `maw ws advance`. Systematic audit of epoch-ref writes vs. worktree HEAD state is warranted.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","state-consistency","rebase","sync"],"size":"s","title":"Workspace epoch ref advanced unconditionally after conflicted rebase and silently on failure"}	blake3:X7P68AHcHZReygeMmMl18SqXy45Ls9QLFU9xs1XHNgY
1776705660172087	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4Ao		item.create	bn-372v	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:320-336 and 152-212\n\n**Issue**: `list_commits_ahead` lists commits via `git rev-list --reverse <epoch>..HEAD`, which includes merge commits. The per-commit replay loop then runs `git cherry-pick --no-commit <sha>` for each entry. `git cherry-pick` rejects merge commits with \"is a merge but no -m option was given\" and returns a non-zero status, which the code at rebase.rs:214-267 treats as a regular \"conflict\" — recording an empty-looking conflict entry, relabeling nonexistent markers, committing empty, and continuing. The merge's actual contribution is never replayed.\n\n**Root Cause**: `rev-list` without `--no-merges` yields the full reachable set. The replay loop has no special case for merge commits — the failed cherry-pick is indistinguishable from a content conflict. `list_conflicted_files` (rebase.rs:354-385) returns an empty list because there are no unmerged index entries, so the \"conflict\" branch runs `git add --all` on a clean worktree and commits an empty rebase commit. The merge's side content is silently dropped.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P2 (data loss — merge commit content lost without reporting; affects any workspace that did a merge on top of its base before sync)\n- Scope: workspaces that contain merge commits (uncommon in ephemeral agent workspaces, common in persistent workspaces pulling in upstream branches)\n- Reproducibility: 100% when the workspace HEAD chain contains any merge commit\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:320-336\nfn list_commits_ahead(ws_path: &Path, epoch_oid: &str) -> Result<Vec<String>> {\n    let range = format!(\"{epoch_oid}..HEAD\");\n    let output = Command::new(\"git\")\n        .args([\"rev-list\", \"--reverse\", &range])   // <-- no --no-merges, no --first-parent\n        .current_dir(ws_path)\n        .output()\n        ...\n```\n\nLoop dispatch at rebase.rs:157-161:\n```rust\nlet cp_output = Command::new(\"git\")\n    .args([\"cherry-pick\", \"--no-commit\", commit_sha])   // <-- no -m <parent>\n    .current_dir(ws_path)\n    .output()\n    ...\n```\n\nThe branch that handles cherry-pick failure at lines 214-267 assumes the failure is a content conflict (it looks for unmerged index entries via `list_conflicted_files`, writes conflict metadata, relabels markers). For a merge-commit failure there are no unmerged entries and no markers — we just commit empty with message `\"rebase: conflict replaying {short_sha} (0 file(s))\"` and move on. The `conflicts` vector gets an entry with an empty path list, and the rebase \"succeeds\".\n\n**Context**: Persistent workspaces (the only kind that would normally hit sync --rebase) may legitimately contain merge commits — for example, pulling a shared branch into the workspace to test integration before merging into default. The current code discards that history silently.\n\n**Related**: No integration tests of the rebase flow exist — only the JSON serialization test at rebase.rs:450-479. A fixture with a merge commit in the ahead range would immediately expose this.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","data-loss","rebase","merge-commits"],"size":"m","title":"sync --rebase silently drops merge commits during cherry-pick replay"}	blake3:WnPlQNiluvB76ZJSJ_F0eqwMEBnRzRIlzxOPSrU7Dtg
1776705684797225	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4Qo		item.create	bn-lc1j	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:413-444\n\n**Issue**: `relabel_conflict_markers` rewrites conflict marker headers in a conflicted file so `maw ws resolve` can match them by name. The final `std::fs::write` is wrapped in `let _ = ...` (line 443), silently discarding any I/O error. If the write fails (permission denied, disk full, read-only FS), the worktree keeps git's original `<<<<<<< HEAD` / `>>>>>>> abc123 (commit msg)` markers but every downstream command assumes relabeled markers exist. Conflict resolution breaks silently.\n\n**Root Cause**: The relabel step is part of the contract that `maw ws resolve --keep epoch` / `--keep <ws-name>` will match markers by name. `maw ws resolve` (resolve.rs) scans for markers like `<<<<<<< epoch` or `>>>>>>> <ws-name>` — if relabeling failed, those tokens never appear in the file and `--keep` returns \"nothing to resolve\" or picks the wrong side.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P2 (conflict resolution UX breaks in a confusing way; user runs `maw ws resolve <ws> --keep epoch`, tool reports success, but the file still contains git's raw markers — manifesting later as a \"commit has conflict markers\" failure or, worse, a merge that pulls the markers forward)\n- Scope: any rebase that produces conflicts on a filesystem where the write can fail (CI runners with tight disk quotas, read-only mounts, permission issues on shared repos)\n- Reproducibility: 100% if the write fails; never in the happy path\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:413-444\npub(super) fn relabel_conflict_markers(ws_path: &Path, rel_path: &str, ws_name: &str) {\n    let full_path = ws_path.join(rel_path);\n    let content = match std::fs::read_to_string(&full_path) {\n        Ok(c) => c,\n        Err(_) => return,           // <-- silent return on read failure\n    };\n\n    let mut output = String::with_capacity(content.len());\n    for line in content.lines() {\n        if line.starts_with(\"<<<<<<<\") {\n            output.push_str(\"<<<<<<< epoch (current)\");\n        } else if line.starts_with(\">>>>>>>\") {\n            output.push_str(&format!(\">>>>>>> {ws_name} (workspace changes)\"));\n        } else {\n            output.push_str(line);\n        }\n        output.push('\\n');\n    }\n\n    let _ = std::fs::write(&full_path, output);   // <-- silent write failure\n}\n```\n\nThe function is `pub(super)` with return type `()`, so callers at rebase.rs:249-250 can't observe failure even if they wanted to.\n\n**Context**: `maw ws resolve` is the documented path for users to handle rebase conflicts (AGENTS.md: \"After resolving, commit and clear conflict state\"). When relabel fails silently, the user follows the instructions literally, gets no conflict list, and either commits with raw markers still in the file or is confused by \"no conflicts to resolve\" on a file that clearly has `<<<<<<<` in it.\n\n**Related**: The file-read-failure branch at line 428 also silently returns. Preserving *some* signal (at least a `tracing::warn!`) would let ops teams notice systemic filesystem issues before they manifest as resolution failures.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","error-handling","rebase","resolve"],"size":"xs","title":"relabel_conflict_markers silently ignores read/write errors, breaking 'maw ws resolve' matching"}	blake3:KPsDzCDfRVMtU0P-j5_5Wgd374sPJxxmUofUg3Sqtm8
1776705710289947	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4go		item.create	bn-2bow	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/capture.rs:359-386\n\n**Issue**: `repo_root_from_worktree` derives the repo root from `git rev-parse --git-common-dir` by taking the first parent directory and applying a special-case for `.manifold` as the final component. The logic assumes either a standard `<root>/.git/` layout or a nested `<root>/.manifold/git/` layout. It does not handle linked worktrees or non-standard layouts, and it returns silently wrong paths in those cases — meaning recovery refs get written into the wrong directory with no error.\n\n**Root Cause**: The heuristic on line 378-383 checks only one level of `.manifold` nesting. For any layout that puts the common git dir inside a differently-named subdirectory (e.g. `<root>/state/git`, `<root>/.git/worktrees/<name>` for a linked worktree that resolves common-dir to the outer `.git`), the computed root is the parent of the common-dir with no `.manifold` unwrap — which may be correct for flat layouts but silently wrong otherwise.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P3 (affects only non-default repo layouts; current deployments are standard, but the function is a single point of truth for where recovery refs are written)\n- Scope: alternate repo layouts, linked worktrees with non-default `--separate-git-dir`, externally-configured manifold locations\n- Reproducibility: depends on layout\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// capture.rs:359-386\nfn repo_root_from_worktree(ws_path: &Path) -> Result<std::path::PathBuf> {\n    let output = Command::new(\"git\")\n        .args([\"rev-parse\", \"--path-format=absolute\", \"--git-common-dir\"])\n        .current_dir(ws_path)\n        .output()\n        .context(\"failed to determine git common dir\")?;\n    ...\n    let common_dir = std::path::PathBuf::from(String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stdout).trim());\n    let mut root = common_dir\n        .parent()\n        .context(\"cannot determine repo root from git common dir\")?\n        .to_path_buf();\n\n    // Support nested common-dir layouts like <root>/.manifold/git\n    if root.file_name().is_some_and(|name| name == \".manifold\") {\n        root = root\n            .parent()\n            .context(\"cannot determine repo root from nested common dir\")?\n            .to_path_buf();\n    }\n\n    Ok(root)\n}\n```\n\nThere is no validation that the computed root actually contains a `ws/` directory or a `.manifold/` directory — the function just trusts the string manipulation.\n\n**Context**: `repo_root_from_worktree` feeds every call to `refs::write_ref` in capture.rs (lines 164 and 268). If it returns the wrong directory, recovery refs are pinned under a stranger's `refs/manifold/recovery/` namespace — potentially leaking workspace snapshots to a parent/sibling repo on the same disk.\n\n**Related**: capture.rs has a `// TODO(gix): replace with a dedicated GitRepo method for repo-root discovery` on line 358 — the comment acknowledges the brittleness. Adding a test with a manifold-layout fixture and a non-manifold layout fixture would pin down intended semantics.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","code-smell","capture","repo-layout"],"size":"s","title":"repo_root_from_worktree heuristic silently returns wrong path on non-standard layouts"}	blake3:Xfsn5Ikb6efnSopXELPf42c3xk-YsmshX7Tw-jLbb7w
1776705730781125	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4wo		item.create	bn-2blj	{"description":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:184-188 and capture.rs:215-247\n\n**Issue**: Multiple sites invoke `git reset [HEAD]` inside rebase/capture loops with `let _ = Command::new(\"git\").args([\"reset\"...]).output();`. These resets are the only thing restoring the index to a clean state between cherry-pick iterations or before returning from a failed capture. If the reset fails (lock contention, unwritable `.git/index`, disk full), the loop proceeds with a dirty index and the next cherry-pick / add applies onto stale staged content — producing phantom changes that silently propagate into the rebase commit or the stash.\n\n**Root Cause**: Unchecked output + unchecked exit status. `Command::output()` itself returns `Result<Output>`; the exit status is another layer. The code ignores both.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P3 (race with the user/other maw processes writing to the index; on a single user machine in the happy path, the reset almost always works — but diagnostic trails are absent when it doesn't)\n- Scope: rebase iterations after a \"no-op\" cherry-pick (rebase.rs:185-188) and capture failure-cleanup (capture.rs:215-220 and 228-232 and 244-247)\n- Reproducibility: intermittent under index lock contention\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:185-188 — after detecting \"no staged changes\", reset the index\nlet _ = Command::new(\"git\")\n    .args([\"reset\", \"HEAD\"])\n    .current_dir(ws_path)\n    .output();\n```\n\n```rust\n// capture.rs:244-247 — after successful stash_create, reset the index\nlet _ = Command::new(\"git\")\n    .args([\"reset\"])\n    .current_dir(ws_path)\n    .output();\n```\n\nAnd two more on the failure paths at capture.rs:215-220 and 228-232. All share the pattern of ignoring both the spawn result and the exit code.\n\n**Context**: In capture.rs, the comment says \"the workspace is about to be destroyed, but be clean anyway\" — so for the destroy path the stale index isn't harmful. But for rebase.rs the workspace is *not* about to be destroyed; the next loop iteration cherry-picks against this index. Stale index ⇒ stale diff ⇒ wrong conflict detection.\n\n**Related**: `let _ = Command...` appears many times across the codebase (see grep); each case should be justified individually. For state-mutating gits (reset, add, commit), a non-zero exit should at minimum produce a `tracing::warn!` — ideally propagate.","kind":"bug","labels":["fresh-eyes","error-handling","rebase","capture"],"size":"xs","title":"Unchecked git reset between cherry-pick / capture iterations can corrupt index silently"}	blake3:5F0Ts5AmqC9LScCyuyUeg25yU63X-KdonBnP4CSUjX4
1776708478587701	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy5Ao		item.update	bn-gjm8	{"field":"title","value":"sync --rebase has iteration-order fidelity gap vs. jj-style structured conflicts"}	blake3:NYCcPCym0qtSGWy67InbbqU8yL3UV0k1iTfxPCYNogk
1776708478592458	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy5Qo		item.update	bn-gjm8	{"field":"description","value":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:218-267\n\n**NOTE (2026-04-20 update)**: The original framing of this bone was wrong. Maw follows the jj model of \"allow the operation, represent the conflict explicitly\" — committing with unresolved conflicts is intentional. The real merge path already gates on unresolved markers via `find_conflicted_files` (see merge.rs:2553-2573), so the \"poison future merges\" risk as originally described is mitigated. Rewriting the bone below to describe the narrower fidelity gap that remains.\n\n**Issue**: `sync --rebase` approximates jj-style \"conflicts as data\" by relabeling `<<<<<<<`/`>>>>>>>` markers and committing the marker-laden files via `git add --all` + `git commit --allow-empty` (rebase.rs:255-266). The commit tree then contains stage-0 blobs with textual markers; the structured form (base/ours/theirs) is captured in parallel into `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/rebase-conflicts.json` before the `add` collapses git's stages 1/2/3.\n\nTwo narrow problems remain inside this model:\n\n1. **Iteration-order fidelity**: The next cherry-pick in the loop runs `git cherry-pick --no-commit <next-sha>` against the marker-polluted HEAD. Git's 3-way merge treats the markers as ordinary content. jj's analogue would re-play the next commit against the *structured* conflict, walking each side. For multi-commit rebases with multiple conflicts, the outcome depends on commit order in ways a structured-conflict rebase would not — a change that touches a marker line can \"merge cleanly\" by selecting one side, silently dropping either the new change or one side of the prior conflict.\n\n2. **Structured form lives only in the sidecar**: Once `git add --all` runs, stages 1/2/3 are collapsed to stage-0. The structured base/ours/theirs exists only in `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/rebase-conflicts.json`. If that sidecar is lost (manual cleanup of `.manifold/`, failed flush, corrupted JSON), `maw ws resolve --keep epoch` / `--keep <ws-name>` falls back to parsing textual markers — which loses the base side entirely, because 2-way marker text has no base representation.\n\n**Root Cause**: maw uses git as the storage layer and `git cherry-pick` as the per-commit engine. Git has no native structured-conflict object, so the implementation splits the representation: structured form in a JSON sidecar, rendered form in the commit tree. jj's analogue keeps both views in strict sync because jj owns the operation machinery end-to-end. `git cherry-pick` doesn't read the sidecar, so intra-rebase iterations drop out of sync with the structured form.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P2 (fidelity only; the merge-time marker gate in merge.rs:2553-2573 prevents escape to `default`)\n- Scope: persistent workspaces doing `sync --rebase` across an epoch advance that has multiple conflicting commits\n- Reproducibility: requires a rebase where two or more consecutive commits conflict on overlapping regions; order-sensitive outcomes are reliable once reproduced\n\n**Evidence**: See original capture of the code paths (rebase.rs:214-267 for the conflict-commit flow, rebase.rs:233-241 for the base/ours/theirs sidecar capture, rebase.rs:157-161 for the next-iteration cherry-pick that reads the marker-polluted HEAD).\n\n**Context**: The merge-time gate at merge.rs:2553-2573 is load-bearing — it scans each source workspace's worktree via `find_conflicted_files` (diff-based detection of newly-added marker lines) and refuses merge unless `--force` is passed. That gate prevents the \"poisons `default`\" scenario. The fidelity gap described here is fully contained within a workspace's own history and its own sync/rebase lifecycle.\n\n**Related**:\n- merge.rs:2553-2573 — marker gate on the real merge path\n- merge.rs:2040-2138 — marker surfacing on `merge --check`\n- resolve.rs:464+ `find_conflicted_files` — diff-based marker scan (ground truth for the gate)\n- rebase.rs tests — only one test exists, a JSON serialization roundtrip. No integration test that exercises multi-conflict ordering.\n\n**Suggested follow-up for triage**: Worth considering whether the next-iteration cherry-pick should consult the sidecar and rebuild index stages 1/2/3 from the structured form before `git cherry-pick` runs — i.e. keep git's stage machinery in sync with the structured record, so the engine's 3-way merge sees real conflict state, not marker bytes."}	blake3:YKt_PUgcZYM0nc7wp_TjX1NnMuFASgfPUqo1ZegkA_4
1776708478594030	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy5go		item.update	bn-gjm8	{"field":"size","value":"m"}	blake3:1oNzs6U27UdR9aoGRfYHiaxwgDFwd02PWM_6J3JKojs
1776708478595078	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy5wo		item.update	bn-gjm8	{"field":"urgency","value":"default"}	blake3:4videyGDehNqoAmLBA_hUz1f9AGyaSOrEinI5PWS9-c
1776708740615304	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy6Ao		item.update	bn-3pkx	{"field":"title","value":"Silent failure on workspace epoch ref write in sync/rebase/advance"}	blake3:NoK5KYXF21b1yxEZOUfOVlsNvZOW-7h6EE2zcXabnX0
1776708740643122	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy6Qo		item.update	bn-3pkx	{"field":"description","value":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:270-274, sync/checks.rs:139-142, advance.rs:166-171\n\n**NOTE (2026-04-20 update)**: The original framing claimed \"advanced unconditionally after conflicted rebase\" was a bug. Under maw's jj-style operating model (see AGENTS.md \"Operating Model: Conflicts Are Data\"), a conflicted workspace is intentionally advanced to the new epoch — the conflict rides along in the sidecar and the worktree. That half of the bone is withdrawn. The remaining concern is narrower and is about error handling, not correctness.\n\n**Issue**: Three sites write the workspace epoch ref with `let _ = manifold_refs::write_ref(root, &epoch_ref, &oid)` after successfully updating the worktree HEAD. If the ref write fails (lock contention, unwritable refs directory, file-lock timeout, transient I/O), the workspace retains its old epoch ref while its worktree HEAD has moved forward. Downstream commands (`maw ws status`, `maw ws list`, `maw ws overlap`, `maw ws merge --check`, `maw ws diff`) read the epoch ref, not HEAD, so they all misreport the workspace as stale-against-old-epoch when it is actually on the new epoch.\n\n**Root Cause**: Three parallel call sites treat the ref write as best-effort, silently discarding errors. No tracing, no warning, no status propagation.\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P3 (happy path is almost always fine; failure modes are rare but confusing when they hit — a workspace shows stale against the epoch it's actually on, and any remediation advice points the user to \"sync\" which would be a no-op)\n- Scope: every sync/rebase/advance on systems with ref lock contention (multiple maw processes, CI parallelism, filesystem with aggressive locking)\n- Reproducibility: intermittent\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:270-274\nif let Ok(oid) = maw_core::model::types::GitOid::new(new_epoch) {\n    let epoch_ref = manifold_refs::workspace_epoch_ref(ws_name);\n    let _ = manifold_refs::write_ref(root, &epoch_ref, &oid);\n}\n```\n\n```rust\n// sync/checks.rs:139-142\nif let Ok(oid) = maw_core::model::types::GitOid::new(epoch_oid) {\n    let epoch_ref = manifold_refs::workspace_epoch_ref(ws_name);\n    let _ = manifold_refs::write_ref(root, &epoch_ref, &oid);\n}\n```\n\n```rust\n// advance.rs:168-171\nif let Ok(oid) = maw_core::model::types::GitOid::new(&new_epoch) {\n    let epoch_ref = manifold_refs::workspace_epoch_ref(name);\n    let _ = manifold_refs::write_ref(&root, &epoch_ref, &oid);\n}\n```\n\n**Context**: At minimum, these writes should emit `tracing::warn!` on failure so ops teams can detect systemic ref-store issues. Consider whether failure to write the ref should also propagate as an error — the worktree is already updated at this point, so returning an error from rebase/sync/advance would leave the caller believing the operation failed when in fact it mostly succeeded. A structured result (e.g. a warning field on the JSON output) may be the right shape.\n\n**Related**: `let _ = ...` on state-mutating operations is pervasive (see earlier bone `bn-2blj`). A systematic audit of which are safe-to-ignore vs. silent-state-corruption is worth doing."}	blake3:0oRlmDbU_JcUT4XPGy3jZ167BYGU9PyNTZl-HvHyPCc
1776708740644371	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy6go		item.update	bn-3pkx	{"field":"size","value":"xs"}	blake3:__JR8lsUM3p7nbDFpjRW5wfZTxg0mprLoKNKnafB0Mk
1776708740645289	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy6wo		item.update	bn-3pkx	{"field":"urgency","value":"default"}	blake3:ulr5XyuOZLBtfDHtNfXtQ_m94LNyJrkyS2M7JJa-WLg
1776708782828122	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy7Ao		item.update	bn-372v	{"field":"title","value":"sync --rebase silently drops merge commits AND escapes every conflict gate"}	blake3:HJ7G9be6e5lJy1eFmmIIktFHu9bfI2TdQ9CY9e7Dcn0
1776708782838877	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy7Qo		item.update	bn-372v	{"field":"description","value":"**File**: ws/default/crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:320-336 and 152-267\n\n**NOTE (2026-04-20 update)**: This bone's severity is actually *higher* than originally filed once considered under maw's jj-style \"conflicts are data\" operating model (see AGENTS.md). In jj, rebase handles merge commits natively by rebasing both sides. Maw's cherry-pick-based implementation drops them entirely — and does so in a way that specifically escapes the merge-time marker gate, unlike all other conflict cases.\n\n**Issue**: `list_commits_ahead` lists commits via `git rev-list --reverse <epoch>..HEAD`, which includes merge commits. The per-commit replay loop runs `git cherry-pick --no-commit <sha>` unconditionally. `git cherry-pick` rejects merge commits with \"is a merge but no -m option was given\". The conflict branch then:\n1. Calls `list_conflicted_files(ws_path)` — returns empty, because there are no unmerged index entries (cherry-pick refused to run, not conflicted)\n2. Iterates the empty conflict_files list (no conflict records pushed, no marker relabeling)\n3. Runs `git add --all` on a clean worktree\n4. Commits empty with message `\"rebase: conflict replaying {short_sha} (0 file(s))\"`\n5. Continues to the next commit\n\nThe merge commit's content never reaches the new base. The sidecar records a conflict with zero files attached (path lists are empty). No textual markers are written anywhere in the worktree. The loop continues as if the rebase handled the merge cleanly.\n\n**Why this escapes every safeguard**:\n- `find_conflicted_files` (resolve.rs:464+) detects newly-added `<<<<<<<` lines via diff. The merge-drop writes no markers → zero false positives, zero true positives for this case → returns empty.\n- `merge.rs:2553-2573` marker gate reads from `find_conflicted_files`, so it also returns empty → allows merge.\n- The rebase-conflicts.json sidecar has a `RebaseConflict` entry with `path: \"\"` (unusual) or the entry is missing if `conflict_files` was empty (see the `for cf in &conflict_files { conflicts.push(...) }` loop in rebase.rs:228-242 — if `conflict_files` is empty, no entry is pushed). So `maw ws status` / `maw ws list` read `rebase_conflicts: 0` and show the workspace as synced.\n\nNet result: a workspace that has silently lost merge-commit content appears clean on every surface, and can be merged into `default`.\n\n**Root Cause**: `rev-list` without `--no-merges` yields the full reachable set. Cherry-pick has no `-m <parent>` option passed. The conflict-handling branch assumes the failure mode is \"unmerged index entries\" (content conflict), not \"refused to run at all\" (merge-commit or empty-base or shallow-history cases).\n\n**Impact**:\n- Severity: P1 (silent data loss that escapes every gate; the sidecar *and* the marker scan *and* the status surface all miss it)\n- Scope: persistent workspaces that contain merge commits in their ahead-of-epoch range. Less common in ephemeral agent workspaces; legitimate use case for persistent workspaces integrating upstream branches or combining sub-branches.\n- Reproducibility: 100% when the workspace HEAD chain contains a merge commit ahead of the old epoch\n\n**Evidence**:\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:320-336\nfn list_commits_ahead(ws_path: &Path, epoch_oid: &str) -> Result<Vec<String>> {\n    let range = format!(\"{epoch_oid}..HEAD\");\n    let output = Command::new(\"git\")\n        .args([\"rev-list\", \"--reverse\", &range])   // no --no-merges, no --first-parent\n        .current_dir(ws_path)\n        .output()\n        ...\n```\n\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:157-161\nlet cp_output = Command::new(\"git\")\n    .args([\"cherry-pick\", \"--no-commit\", commit_sha])   // no -m <parent>\n    .current_dir(ws_path)\n    .output()\n```\n\n```rust\n// rebase.rs:216-242 — the empty-conflict-files path\nlet conflict_files = list_conflicted_files(ws_path);   // returns [] for merge-commit refusal\n// ...\nfor cf in &conflict_files {         // iterates empty list\n    conflicts.push(RebaseConflict { ... });   // never executes\n}\n```\n\n**Context**: Under the jj-style operating model, conflicts should be first-class data that rides with the workspace. A merge commit that can't be cleanly rebased is a legitimate conflict shape (left side vs right side of the original merge, each now needing to be rebased onto the new epoch). The current code neither represents this shape nor signals its presence — it silently pretends the rebase succeeded. That is a direct violation of the \"conflicts as data\" principle.\n\n**Possible directions** (for triage, not this bone):\n- Filter merge commits from the ahead list with `--no-merges` and record them as unrebaseable in the sidecar, producing an explicit \"merge commit dropped\" conflict record\n- Or reconstruct the merge on the new base by rebasing both sides independently and replaying the merge (closer to jj's native semantics)\n- Either way, ensure `find_conflicted_files` or an equivalent gate can detect the situation so `maw ws merge` refuses\n\n**Related**:\n- No integration tests exist for the rebase flow (rebase.rs:450-479 is JSON roundtrip only). A fixture with `base -> A -> merge(A, B)` in the ahead range would catch this immediately.\n- Same root shape (cherry-pick failure ≠ content conflict) could affect empty commits, commits with no parent (initial-commit replay), shallow-repo ancestors."}	blake3:QJbFygWrX4cLQXC11vKVg-Cj0NA8-HD8TA1CbfSE5Mg
1776708782839850	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy7go		item.update	bn-372v	{"field":"size","value":"l"}	blake3:TUg-CCz2cEJUMAZFDPPOo-BOhd6igu18yGcbLugjlf0
