1776724099014405	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyjQs		item.create	bn-2xgi	{"description":"**Goal**: Replace `sync --rebase`'s `git cherry-pick` loop with iterative calls into the structured-conflict merge engine in `maw-core::merge`. Close the iteration-order fidelity gap identified in bn-gjm8 and eliminate 18 `Command::new(\"git\")` shell-outs in `sync/rebase.rs`.\n\n**Why**: Maw's operating model is \"conflicts are data\" (jj-style, see `AGENTS.md`). The current rebase implementation bypasses `maw-core::merge` and goes straight to `git cherry-pick`, which operates on textual markers between iterations. The structured conflict representation (`ConflictAtom`, per-side content, etc.) that already exists in `maw-core::model::conflict` is not consulted, so multi-commit rebases with consecutive conflicts become order-sensitive and lossy.\n\n**Plan**: See `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md` in this workspace (bn-gjm8). 7 phases; Phase 0 (scout) already complete. Hard cut to new code path — no legacy flag. Sibling bone migrates `maw ws resolve` to consume the new `ConflictTree` sidecar; ships in the same release.\n\n**Exit criteria**:\n- `rebase.rs` contains zero `Command::new(\"git\")` calls.\n- `sync --rebase` produces one rebased commit per original commit, preserving original commit messages and ahead-of-epoch commit count.\n- Executable bit, symlinks round-trip through replay.\n- bn-372v integration test passes with stronger guarantees (merge commits natively represented instead of stubs).\n- The \"unrelated unilateral edit applied to a pre-existing conflict\" fidelity property holds (Phase 7 test).\n- bn-gjm8 closed.","kind":"goal","labels":["gjm8","refactor","gix-migration","structured-conflicts"],"size":"xl","title":"Route sync --rebase through maw-core::merge (structured conflict engine)","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:bfKvrkEWGmo0-2Na5YSFf0RCMjmHuf-P0a9RPFguXXg
1776724117947546	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyjgs		item.create	bn-3m2q	{"description":"**Parent goal**: bn-2xgi. Plan: `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md` in workspace bn-gjm8.\n\n**Scope**: Land the core data types that the rest of the refactor depends on.\n\n**Deliverables**:\n- `ConflictTree` struct in `maw-core::merge::types` with serde support. Fields: `clean: BTreeMap<PathBuf, MaterializedEntry>`, `conflicts: BTreeMap<PathBuf, Conflict>`, `base_epoch: EpochId`.\n- `MaterializedEntry` struct with `{ mode: EntryMode, oid: GitOid }`.\n- `apply_unilateral_patchset(tree: ConflictTree, patch: PatchSet) → ConflictTree` skeleton covering ONLY the non-conflicted-path cases (path in `tree.clean`, path not in tree → add to `tree.clean`). Conflict-bearing paths return the tree unchanged for now — Phase 2 extends this.\n- Unit tests:\n  - clean-apply replaces a clean blob (mode preserved)\n  - clean-apply on an unrelated path adds it to `tree.clean`\n  - clean-apply deletes a clean path\n  - mode round-trips for blob/executable/symlink\n\n**Definition of done**: `cargo test -p maw-core` passes. `ConflictTree` serdes to stable JSON. No changes to call sites yet.","kind":"task","labels":["gjm8","phase-1"],"parent":"bn-2xgi","size":"s","title":"Phase 1 — ConflictTree + MaterializedEntry scaffolding","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:1js4bH0FIgP1mjylGPGAM2-AKLk8IQzirjug6b-Xsfc
1776724135086602	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyjws		item.create	bn-1n4i	{"description":"**Parent goal**: bn-2xgi. Plan: `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md`. Blocked by: Phase 1 (bn-3m2q).\n\n**Scope**: Make `apply_unilateral_patchset` handle conflict-bearing paths — the core fidelity fix.\n\n**Deliverables**:\n- Extend `apply_unilateral_patchset` to handle paths in `tree.conflicts`:\n  - For `Conflict::Content`: walk each `ConflictAtom`, apply the incoming `FileChange` to each `ConflictSide.content`. Result is a new `Conflict::Content` with each side = `side + patch`.\n  - For `Conflict::AddAdd`: same pattern — apply patch to each add-side.\n  - For `Conflict::ModifyDelete`: apply patch to the modify-side; delete-side stays.\n  - For `Conflict::DivergentRename`: apply patch to each rename-target.\n- Side-convergence detection: after patching, if all sides of a `Conflict` become identical, collapse the entry back to `tree.clean` with the converged content.\n- Explicit handling (not silent flattening) for non-content conflict shapes: chmod-conflict, type-change-conflict, submodule-boundary. For V1, emit an explicit `UnhandledConflictShape` sentinel rather than silently dropping data. Document in plan notes.\n- Unit tests covering: patch hits conflicted path; side convergence → collapse to clean; patch adds new divergence within an existing conflict; patch against `ModifyDelete`; patch against `AddAdd`.\n- Property test: for any `PatchSet` that touches only non-conflicted paths, `apply_unilateral_patchset` is a no-op on the `conflicts` map.\n\n**Definition of done**: `cargo test -p maw-core` passes. Code coverage on `apply_unilateral_patchset` ≥ 90%.","kind":"task","labels":["gjm8","phase-2"],"parent":"bn-2xgi","size":"m","title":"Phase 2 — apply_unilateral_patchset handles conflict-bearing paths","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:Pq0XVeBiJQXhhwPBow4DibP2dTlPUAKrT58SanD6r7A
1776724154904133	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEykAs		item.create	bn-22zz	{"description":"**Parent goal**: bn-2xgi. Plan: `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md`. No dependencies — can run in parallel with Phases 1–2.\n\n**Scope**: Add three small primitives to `maw-git::GitRepo` that the new rebase pipeline needs. These are net-new GitRepo surface, should cleanly match the existing trait style (object-safe, gix-backed).\n\n**Deliverables**:\n\n1. **`walk_commits(from: GitOid, to: GitOid, reverse: bool) → Vec<GitOid>`**\n   - Returns commits in `from..to` range (ancestors of `to` not reachable from `from`).\n   - `reverse: true` → oldest-first (for replay order).\n   - Implementation: `gix::Repository::rev_walk()`.\n   - Tests: empty range, linear history, history with merges, single commit.\n\n2. **Rename-aware `diff_trees`**:\n   - `ChangeType::Renamed { from: PathBuf }` variant is already defined in `types.rs:285` but never emitted by `diff_impl.rs`.\n   - Either (a) extend the existing `diff_trees` to emit renames when similarity ≥ default threshold, OR (b) add a sibling `diff_trees_with_renames(old, new, similarity: u32) → Vec<DiffEntry>` to avoid breaking existing callers.\n   - Recommend (b) — keep `diff_trees` a pure tree diff; rebase explicitly opts into rename detection.\n   - Use `gix::diff::tree::with_rewrites`.\n   - Tests: pure rename (similarity=100); rename + edit (similarity≥50); rename + heavy edit (below threshold → emitted as delete+add).\n\n3. **`set_head(oid: GitOid)` or `checkout_commit(oid: GitOid, workdir: &Path)`**:\n   - Updates `HEAD` to point at `oid` (detached).\n   - Rebase needs this after each iteration's commit to advance the worktree without using `git checkout`.\n   - Tests: detached HEAD advancement, repeated calls, HEAD-ref-file format correct.\n\n**Definition of done**: All three methods implemented, `cargo test -p maw-git` passes, object-safety preserved (no generics, no `Self` returns), docs match trait-level conventions.\n\n**Not in scope**: refactoring existing callers to use `walk_commits`. That's out-of-scope cleanup.","kind":"task","labels":["gjm8","phase-6","gix"],"parent":"bn-2xgi","size":"m","title":"Phase 6 — GitRepo primitives: walk_commits, rename-aware diff_trees, set_head","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:y-VAeDf5HXcog6KauUH0AUbvB27Bvu1eWOmJMJD7pcQ
1776724175280579	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEykQs		item.create	bn-1lvo	{"description":"**Parent goal**: bn-2xgi. Plan: `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md`. Blocked by: Phase 6 (rename-aware `diff_trees`).\n\n**Scope**: Produce the `PatchSet` inputs that the merge engine consumes, from historical commit ranges. Replaces the current shell-out `git rev-list` + `git hash-object` pattern.\n\n**Deliverables**:\n\n- `diff_patchset(repo: &dyn GitRepo, from_oid: &GitOid, to_oid: &GitOid, workspace_id: &WorkspaceId) → Result<PatchSet>` in `maw-core::merge`.\n  - Calls `repo.diff_trees_with_renames(from, to, similarity)` (from Phase 6).\n  - For each `DiffEntry`, translates into a `FileChange::with_identity(path, kind, content, file_id, blob)`.\n  - `content`: read via `repo.read_blob(oid)` for adds/modifications; `None` for deletes.\n  - `blob`: the `new_oid` from `DiffEntry`.\n  - `file_id`: for renamed entries, synthesize a stable `FileId` that matches across the rename (e.g. hash of `old_oid` or `old_path`); for non-renamed, use `file_id_from_blob(new_oid)` (existing helper in `diff.rs:260`).\n  - `kind`: `ChangeKind::Added` / `Modified` / `Deleted`; renames become `Modified` on the new path (with the `file_id` carrying the identity).\n\n- Preserve mode information: `DiffEntry.new_mode` → needs to flow through as part of the patch so Phase 4's materialization can write it. The current `FileChange` struct doesn't carry mode — either extend it to include `mode: Option<EntryMode>` (preferred, one-line addition) or tuck mode into a sidecar map. Decide at implementation time; lean toward the field addition.\n\n- Tests against fixture repos:\n  - Add-only commit range\n  - Modify-only range\n  - Delete-only range\n  - Range with a rename (similarity=100)\n  - Range with rename + small edit\n  - Range with chmod-only change\n  - Range crossing a merge commit (should emit the merge commit's delta-vs-each-parent shape; Phase 5 decides how to consume)\n\n**Definition of done**: `cargo test -p maw-core merge::diff_patchset` passes. The function is pure (no I/O outside `repo` calls), deterministic.","kind":"task","labels":["gjm8","phase-3"],"parent":"bn-2xgi","size":"m","title":"Phase 3 — diff_patchset: historical patch extraction helper","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:LVbJmPdjqnzasb8fadN3Zjfab6ulegcxvBLbk47AmpM
1776724194841291	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEykgs		item.create	bn-11b0	{"description":"**Parent goal**: bn-2xgi. Plan: `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md`. Blocked by: Phase 2 (bn-1n4i).\n\n**Scope**: Turn a `ConflictTree` into something the rebase pipeline can commit — a full set of tree entries + new blobs to write.\n\n**Deliverables**:\n\n- `materialize(tree: &ConflictTree) → Result<MaterializedOutput>` in `maw-core::merge`.\n  - `MaterializedOutput { entries: BTreeMap<PathBuf, MaterializedEntry>, new_blobs: Vec<(GitOid, Vec<u8>)> }`.\n  - For each path in `tree.clean`: emit the `MaterializedEntry` directly.\n  - For each path in `tree.conflicts`: render the conflict into a diff3-style marker blob, add to `new_blobs`, emit a `MaterializedEntry` pointing at the new blob OID with `mode = EntryMode::Blob`.\n  - Marker rendering reuses the existing `<<<<<<< epoch (current)` / `>>>>>>> <ws-name> (workspace changes)` label scheme so V1 `maw ws resolve` still scans them correctly.\n\n- `write_legacy_sidecar(ws_path: &Path, tree: &ConflictTree) → Result<()>` — projects `ConflictTree` to the flat `RebaseConflicts` schema in `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/rebase-conflicts.json`. One `RebaseConflict` entry per conflicted path with `base`/`ours`/`theirs` populated from the structured form. Keeps V1 resolver working unchanged.\n\n- `write_conflict_tree_sidecar(ws_path: &Path, tree: &ConflictTree) → Result<()>` — also writes the richer `ConflictTree` JSON to `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/conflict-tree.json` for the sibling-bone resolver migration and for diagnostics.\n\n- Unit tests:\n  - materialize a clean tree → round-trips through `read_tree`-style verification\n  - materialize a tree with one `Conflict::Content` → produces a blob with diff3 markers\n  - materialize preserves executable bit on a clean exec file\n  - legacy sidecar is deserializable by current `read_rebase_conflicts` (resolve.rs)\n  - round-trip: materialize → read_blob → parse markers → matches original sides\n\n**Definition of done**: `cargo test -p maw-core merge::materialize` passes. Legacy sidecar projection is byte-compatible with what the current resolver reads.","kind":"task","labels":["gjm8","phase-4"],"parent":"bn-2xgi","size":"s","title":"Phase 4 — materialize + sidecar projections (new ConflictTree schema + legacy compat)","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:j4Z2JTSlU2mrUz-Ng84YjvzDr1E01gsmPcndaj52OQA
1776724218712093	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEykws		item.create	bn-elj0	{"description":"**Parent goal**: bn-2xgi. Plan: `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md`. Blocked by: Phase 2 (bn-1n4i), Phase 3 (bn-1lvo), Phase 4 (bn-11b0), Phase 6 (bn-22zz).\n\n**Scope**: Replace `rebase_workspace` in `sync/rebase.rs` with the pipeline that uses `apply_unilateral_patchset`, `materialize`, and `GitRepo` primitives. The big integration.\n\n**Deliverables**:\n\n- Replace `rebase_workspace` body with the pseudocode from the plan doc (§\"What needs to change in `sync/rebase.rs`\"):\n  - Use `repo.walk_commits(old_epoch, head, reverse=true)` — NO `git rev-list` shell-out.\n  - Seed state with a two-way `ConflictTree` from `Y_delta` + `A_delta` (diff_patchset calls).\n  - Iterate remaining commits: `apply_unilateral_patchset` for single-parent, `apply_merge` for merge commits (native handling — bn-372v's stub mechanism is deleted).\n  - Commit per iteration via `repo.create_commit(tree_oid, &[parent], original_message, None)` — parent-chained, preserves commit count and original messages.\n  - Advance HEAD via `repo.set_head` — NO `git checkout --detach` shell-out.\n  - Write both sidecar schemas via Phase 4 helpers.\n\n- Delete:\n  - The stub-file mechanism added for bn-372v (`record_merge_commit_drop`, `record_cherry_pick_refusal`, `dropped_stub_rel_path`, `format_dropped_stub`, `.manifold/rebase-dropped/` directory). Merge commits are now natively handled.\n  - `relabel_conflict_markers` and its call sites (markers now come from `materialize`).\n  - `list_commits_ahead` (replaced by `walk_commits`).\n  - `get_commit_message` (inlined via `read_commit(sha).message`).\n  - `list_conflicted_files`, `read_conflict_stages` (no longer needed — structured conflicts carry side data directly).\n\n- Verify: `rebase.rs` contains ZERO `Command::new(\"git\")` calls after this phase. Grep for it in CI / Definition of done.\n\n- Preserve existing tests:\n  - bn-372v integration test in `tests/merge_rebase_reconcile.rs` must still pass (it asserts merge commits are detected + marker gate rejects the merge; under the new impl, the workspace will have a real structured conflict with markers rendered, so the gate still trips).\n  - Any other rebase-flow tests in the project must still pass.\n\n**Definition of done**:\n- `grep -n 'Command::new(\"git\")' crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs` returns nothing.\n- `cargo test -p maw-cli sync` passes.\n- `cargo test --test merge_rebase_reconcile` passes.\n- Manual smoke test: create a workspace, do 2 commits, advance epoch, run `maw ws sync --rebase` — observe 2 rebased commits with original messages.","kind":"task","labels":["gjm8","phase-5"],"parent":"bn-2xgi","size":"l","title":"Phase 5 — rebase integration: replace cherry-pick loop, delete stubs, zero git shell-outs","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:B-OpP_SHedqYeKhkW2BkXeGcbNGK44wBtp6oDGBGo3c
1776724242170265	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylAs		item.create	bn-28rd	{"description":"**Parent goal**: bn-2xgi. Plan: `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md`. Blocked by: Phase 5 (bn-elj0).\n\n**Scope**: Lock in the observable contract and the narrow fidelity property the refactor is meant to preserve / deliver. Explicitly NOT an ordering-invariance test — rebase is order-sensitive by design.\n\n**Deliverables** — tests in `tests/` under a new file `sync_rebase_semantics.rs` (or colocate with existing rebase tests):\n\n1. **Commit-count preservation**:\n   - Workspace with N non-conflicting commits ahead of old epoch; rebase onto new epoch; assert `rev-list --count <new_epoch>..HEAD == N`.\n   - Test N=1, N=3.\n\n2. **Original commit messages preserved**:\n   - Three commits with messages \"feat: A\", \"fix: B\", \"chore: C\"; rebase; assert new HEAD chain has the same three messages in order.\n\n3. **No content drops**:\n   - Workspace modifies file X in commit A, file Y in commit B; rebase; assert the final tree contains both X and Y with the workspace's final content.\n\n4. **Mode preservation**:\n   - Workspace commits that touch an executable file; rebase; assert the resulting tree has the exec bit.\n   - Workspace commits a symlink; rebase; assert the resulting tree has mode 120000.\n\n5. **Merge-commit preservation (bn-372v regression)**:\n   - Ensure existing `sync_rebase_marks_workspace_conflicted_on_merge_commit` test in `tests/merge_rebase_reconcile.rs` still passes. Under the new impl, the merge commit is natively represented as a structured conflict rather than a stub file, so the assertions about \"merge commit detected + marker gate rejects merge\" may need minor adjustment — update the test to accept either representation explicitly.\n\n6. **Narrow fidelity property**:\n   - Setup: workspace has commits A → B where A conflicts with the new epoch on file F, and B modifies an unrelated file G.\n   - Rebase.\n   - Assert: the `ConflictTree` sidecar shows F as conflicted with the original A-side content intact; G is clean with B's content.\n   - The key property: B's unilateral edit on G does not corrupt F's conflict — structured side data for F survives across iteration 2.\n\n**Definition of done**: all tests pass. The bn-372v test passes. The commit-count and message-preservation tests would have failed under my originally-drafted (collapse-to-one-commit) pseudocode, so their passing proves Change #1 from the review was correctly applied.","kind":"task","labels":["gjm8","phase-7","testing"],"parent":"bn-2xgi","size":"s","title":"Phase 7 — semantics-preservation + narrow fidelity tests","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:fVL2qST5g59d7THm0OySrh1X9YAYzS-JTqn-GjAYKr8
1776724264909824	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylQs		item.create	bn-3rah	{"description":"**Parent goal**: bn-2xgi (sibling of Phase 1–7). Plan: `notes/sync-rebase-through-merge-engine.md`. Release-blocking: must ship in same release as gjm8, but does NOT block gjm8 merging to main.\n\n**Why separate from gjm8**: Keeps the gjm8 refactor focused on the rebase pipeline. This bone migrates the *consumer* side.\n\n**Current state after gjm8 lands**:\n- `sync --rebase` writes BOTH a legacy `rebase-conflicts.json` (flat) AND a new `conflict-tree.json` (structured).\n- `maw ws resolve` still reads the legacy schema and operates on textual markers in the worktree.\n- The richer structured form is unused except for diagnostics.\n\n**Scope**:\n\n- Teach `maw ws resolve` to prefer `conflict-tree.json` when present:\n  - `--list` enumerates conflicts from the structured form (paths + conflict shape + atom count).\n  - `--keep epoch` / `--keep <ws-name>` / `--keep both` operate per-atom rather than per-file.\n  - Atom-level resolution: when a single file has multiple `ConflictAtom`s (localized regions), each can be resolved independently.\n  - When the structured form is absent (workspace rebased by an older version of maw), fall back to the legacy marker-scan path.\n\n- Update output surfaces (`maw ws conflicts`, `maw ws status`) to report atom counts alongside file counts.\n\n- Migration: for any existing `rebase-conflicts.json` without a companion `conflict-tree.json`, leave alone — keep the legacy path working for in-flight workspaces from before this release.\n\n- Tests:\n  - Resolve a workspace written by new `sync --rebase` (has both sidecars); verify structured path is taken.\n  - Resolve a workspace written by legacy `sync --rebase` (legacy sidecar only); verify fallback works.\n  - Per-atom resolution: file with two conflict atoms, resolve each with a different `--keep` choice.\n\n**Definition of done**:\n- `cargo test -p maw-cli resolve` passes including new per-atom tests.\n- Manual check: a workspace created in the new world supports atom-level resolution; a workspace from the old world still resolves via markers.\n- Release checklist notes both bones together.\n\n**Not in scope**:\n- Deprecating the legacy sidecar format. Both schemas continue to be written by `sync --rebase` for at least one more release for rollback safety.\n- UI / TUI changes for atom visualization. If valuable, file separately.","kind":"task","labels":["gjm8","resolve","release-blocker"],"parent":"bn-2xgi","size":"m","title":"Migrate maw ws resolve to consume ConflictTree sidecar (per-atom resolution)"}	blake3:zUGYym1bDKipLuDhXfa32n145stM81zYZTYmnN8AIYg
