1776730662649023	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEywws		item.create	bn-324m	{"description":"**Issue**: After `maw ws sync --rebase` produces a conflict, the materialized working-tree file is nearly useless for humans:\n- Both the start and end markers are labeled `epoch` (start: `<<<<<<< epoch (current)`, end: `>>>>>>> epoch (workspace changes)`) — the end marker should say the workspace name, not `epoch`.\n- The actual conflicting content is NOT inlined — instead the file contains stub text like `(epoch content not inlined in V1 structured render)` and `# side: epoch  @  <blobsha>` / `# side: feature  @  <blobsha>`.\n\nThis means the agent literally cannot see either side's content just by reading the file. They must run `maw ws resolve --keep <side>` blind, or cat the blob manually.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\necho \"line0\" > ws/default/shared.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feature --from main\necho \"ws-A\" > ws/feature/shared.txt && maw exec feature -- git add -A && maw exec feature -- git commit -m \"ws: A\"\necho \"ws-B\" > ws/feature/shared.txt && maw exec feature -- git add -A && maw exec feature -- git commit -m \"ws: B\"\necho \"epoch-line\" > ws/default/shared.txt && maw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m default\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feature\ncat ws/feature/shared.txt\n```\n\n**Expected** (a classic diff3-style rendering):\n\n```\n<<<<<<< epoch\nepoch-line\n||||||| base\nline0\n=======\nws-B\n>>>>>>> feature\n```\n\n**Actual**:\n\n```\n# structured conflict at shared.txt\n# base blob: d0a234c6d7279b8c0d5d0f17882eeffd888c40d6\n\n<<<<<<< epoch (current)\n(epoch content not inlined in V1 structured render)\n||||||| base\n(base blob: d0a234c6d7279b8c0d5d0f17882eeffd888c40d6)\n=======\n# side: epoch  @  1df952d9e09791a0390f6a6612263c24e2ff3717\n# side: feature  @  62d96ac3c5887da3a8f8e841fbd694f23e391aad\n>>>>>>> epoch (workspace changes)\n```\n\nTwo problems in one: (1) content is stubbed out with placeholder strings, (2) the `>>>>>>>` label says `epoch` instead of the workspace name. A user reading this file in their editor has no way to even tell which workspace their change ended up in.\n\n**Impact**: Medium-high. The resolve `--keep` path works mechanically, but anyone who tries to open the conflicted file in an editor (or who wants to hand-merge in vim / have their agent reason about the content) gets back placeholder garbage. Makes the rebase-as-data flow much less useful than the UI suggests.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: `V1 structured render` path is writing side labels and placeholder text instead of resolving the blob SHAs back to content. The closing marker reuse of `epoch` is probably a copy/paste bug in the render routine.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"m","title":"Rebase conflict markers show placeholder text, both ends labeled 'epoch'"}	blake3:_62hXtFuPlR3XnneO5gYTLkfOaNDAWJD-x6T1wFNRfI
1776730732589275	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxAs		item.create	bn-7mbe	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws sync --rebase` silently flattens merge commits into single-parent commits. The \"replayed\" commit keeps the merge's commit message but loses the second parent — so the history shape is destroyed without any warning.\n\nThe UX output does indicate `Replayed (merge commit)`, which hints the engine knows it's a merge, but the resulting commit has exactly one parent; git no longer sees it as a merge.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\nmaw ws create feat --from main\ncd ws/feat\ngit checkout -b side\necho \"side\" > s.txt && git add s.txt && git commit -m \"side: s.txt\"\ngit checkout bfc0154   # original epoch sha\ngit merge --no-ff side -m \"merge side into feat\"\ncd -\necho foo > ws/default/f.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"default: f\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\n# The original merge commit had 2 parents; the new one has 1:\nmaw exec feat -- git cat-file -p HEAD | grep -c ^parent     # prints 1\nmaw exec feat -- git log --graph --oneline                  # fully linear\n```\n\n**Expected**: One of\n1. Rebase refuses and says \"merge commits in ahead range not supported; flatten first with `git rebase --root` or drop the merge.\"\n2. Rebase actually replays the merge correctly (preserve 2-parent shape via `--rebase-merges`).\n3. Rebase notifies the user it is flattening.\n\n**Actual**: Silent linearization. Output text says `Replayed (merge commit)` but the resulting tree is fully linear, original merge topology is gone.\n\n**Impact**: Low for typical linear-workflow agents but surprising for users who do branching inside their workspace. \"Replayed (merge commit)\" is actively misleading because it implies structure is preserved.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: cherry-pick-style replay always produces single-parent commits. The engine detects the merge (hence the log message) but then does the normal cherry-pick anyway. Either fix the message or actually handle merges.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"s","title":"Rebase silently flattens merge commits despite 'Replayed (merge commit)' output"}	blake3:AULOqfq7eeu20MJp8EkRYNpYVGg-ek6IHxhZ7ZPvFwA
1776730766056733	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxQs		item.create	bn-3525	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws sync --rebase` silently drops file renames when the renamed-from file was also modified in the epoch. The replayed commit keeps its original message but its tree is effectively empty — the rename is simply gone.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\necho hello > ws/default/a.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"base a.txt\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\ncd ws/feat && git mv a.txt b.txt && git commit -m \"ws: rename a->b\"\ncd -\necho \"hello modified\" > ws/default/a.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"default: modify a\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\n```\n\n**Expected** (pick one):\n1. The rename wins, content follows: `ws/feat/b.txt` contains `\"hello modified\"`, `a.txt` is gone. (Git's default `ort` merge strategy does exactly this for rename/modify.)\n2. Rebase reports a rename conflict and marks the workspace as conflicted so the user can choose.\n\nEither is reasonable. Silent data loss is not.\n\n**Actual**:\n- `ws/feat/a.txt` exists with the epoch's modified content.\n- `ws/feat/b.txt` does NOT exist.\n- `git log --oneline` still shows the commit \"ws: rename a->b\".\n- `git show --stat HEAD` shows **no file changes** — the replayed commit is effectively empty despite its message claiming a rename.\n- No conflict is reported. No warning is emitted. The rebase output says \"Replayed cleanly.\"\n\nSo the user loses work and has no indication. The commit message becomes a lie.\n\n**Impact**: HIGH (data loss, no warning). Anyone using rename-heavy refactors is vulnerable. Urgency could reasonably be bumped; leaving default but flagging.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: The rebase engine is computing patches via raw blob-diff paths without rename detection. When it reapplies the `a.txt -> b.txt` move to a tree where `a.txt` already has different content, the rename half fails silently and the add-side is dropped too, leaving a net no-op commit.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"m","title":"Rebase silently drops renames when the renamed-from file was modified in epoch","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:ZnQQU_Y0Va9Vlx_9dv52MxMrFQQikaDTp-_xMgbyj6s
1776730796627409	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxgs		item.create	bn-2o1y	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws sync --rebase` does not preserve the executable bit on new executables added by the workspace. The working tree ends up with `0755` but the commit tree stores `100644`, leaving the workspace dirty after a \"clean\" rebase.\n\nThis is the same class of bug the bn-nsz0 change was supposed to fix. Either that fix didn't cover the rebase path, or it regressed.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\necho noop > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\nprintf '#!/bin/bash\\necho hi\\n' > ws/feat/script.sh\nchmod 0755 ws/feat/script.sh\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \"ws: add executable script.sh\"\necho changed > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"default: modify noop\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\n```\n\n**Expected**: Replayed commit has `script.sh` with git mode `100755`. Working tree is clean after rebase.\n\n**Actual**:\n- `git ls-tree HEAD script.sh` → `100644 blob ... script.sh`  (exec bit lost)\n- Working tree on disk still has `0755`\n- `git status` shows a dirty working tree with mode change `old mode 100644 / new mode 100755`\n\nSo the rebase quietly demoted the file mode in the commit. A user running `maw ws merge feat` after this would merge a non-executable script.sh into default.\n\n**Impact**: Medium (data loss of file metadata, and silent disagreement between tree and index). Very easy to miss because the working tree looks fine.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: Rebase engine reconstructs trees from blob-only patches and writes all entries back as `100644`. The exec-bit plumbing added in bn-nsz0 covers merge-to-default but not the cherry-pick path used by `--rebase`.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"m","title":"Rebase drops executable bit on new executables (regresses bn-nsz0 for --rebase path)"}	blake3:FzxsT3y-sW9lqP4YLmlMCWN1-JKczriojd3fg6WWLtA
1776730819782022	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxws		item.create	bn-3gbi	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws sync --rebase` silently converts symlinks into regular files. The symlink's target path becomes the file contents, and git mode changes from `120000` to `100644`.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\necho base > ws/default/target.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"base target\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\ncd ws/feat && ln -s target.txt link && git add link && git commit -m \"ws: add symlink\"\ncd -\necho modified > ws/default/target.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"default: modify target\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\nls -la ws/feat/link\nmaw exec feat -- git ls-tree HEAD link\ncat ws/feat/link\n```\n\n**Expected**: After rebase, `link` is still a symlink pointing at `target.txt`. Git mode is `120000`. Running the symlink resolves to the (now modified) target content.\n\n**Actual**:\n- `ls -la` shows `-rw-r--r--` (regular file, no `l` prefix)\n- `git ls-tree HEAD link` returns `100644 blob ... link` (regular file in tree)\n- `cat ws/feat/link` prints `target.txt` — the symlink's target literal is now the file's content\n- Output says \"Replayed cleanly\" with no warning\n\n**Impact**: Medium-high. Symlinks are uncommon in many repos but critical in some (monorepos with internal links, docs with relative links, toolchain symlinks). Silently destroying them with no warning is bad, and a `--rebase` user who merges back to default would push a regular-file \"link\" containing its old target path as content.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: The rebase engine reads blob content via `cat-file blob` but writes everything with mode `100644`. Symlink mode (`120000`) is a separate code path that isn't handled during the replay. Same class of bug as the exec-bit loss (bn-2o1y).","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"m","title":"Rebase converts symlinks to regular files containing the target path as text"}	blake3:5adIy49aalZ_7cDeRmlbjo_1wsOIBIUm36LFHHKOYGo
1776730842557900	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyyAs		item.create	bn-3oau	{"description":"**Issue**: The `maw ws merge` conflict-marker gate false-triggers on files that legitimately contain conflict-marker-looking strings (e.g. a markdown tutorial, a test fixture, a commit-message-template doc). The rebase succeeds cleanly, but then `merge` refuses to ship the workspace.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\necho base > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\ncat > ws/feat/tutorial.md <<'MD'\n# Merge conflicts\n<<<<<<< mine\nmy version\n||||||| base\noriginal\n=======\ntheir version\n>>>>>>> theirs\nMD\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \"ws: tutorial\"\necho new > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m default\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat                          # reports \"Replayed cleanly\"\nmaw ws merge feat --into default --message \"x\"    # refuses\n```\n\n**Expected**: Merge proceeds because the file had these markers from the start; they are not the result of a failed merge. At minimum the gate should check whether the file actually has an unresolved conflict in the index (git's stage 1/2/3 entries) rather than grepping blob content.\n\n**Actual**:\n```\nError: Workspace 'feat' has 1 unresolved conflict marker(s) in its worktree:\n  - tutorial.md\n  Resolve them first (strip <<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>> markers and commit), then retry.\n  To force merge anyway: maw ws merge feat --into default --force\n```\n\nThe user has to `--force` to ship legitimate content.\n\n**Expected heuristic**: Only flag files whose index has merge stages (git status conflict state), or whose path is listed in `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/conflict-tree.json`. Pure textual grep for `<<<<<<<` is too broad.\n\n**Impact**: Low-medium. Annoying false positive for agents writing docs, test fixtures for conflict tooling, or, ironically, maw's own tests. `--force` workaround exists, but then `--force` also bypasses legitimate conflicts, so it's a poor fallback.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial"],"size":"s","title":"Merge conflict-marker gate false-triggers on content that happens to contain <<<<<<<"}	blake3:KAqBOkZ2_O7omaEtlWOiWcV0PILlvCLzrjJI37Xw0C8
1776730880624407	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyyQs		item.create	bn-ad5z	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws sync --rebase` writes textual \"structured conflict\" placeholder text into the working-tree copy of a **binary file** when there's a conflict. The original binary bytes on disk are replaced with ASCII commentary (including `<<<<<<< epoch (current)`, `(epoch content not inlined in V1 structured render)`, blob shas, etc).\n\nAny tool that opens the file between rebase and resolve sees garbage. If the user `git add -A` and commits before resolving, they permanently commit the corrupt text blob — image.png is now a plaintext conflict explanation.\n\nThe underlying blobs are still in git, so `--keep feat` / `--keep epoch` recovers. But the intermediate on-disk state is actively destructive.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\nprintf '\\x89PNG\\r\\n\\x1a\\n\\x00\\x00A\\x00\\x01base' > ws/default/image.png\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\nprintf '\\x89PNG\\r\\n\\x1a\\n\\x00\\x00A\\x00\\x01wsver' > ws/feat/image.png\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \"ws: modify png\"\nprintf '\\x89PNG\\r\\n\\x1a\\n\\x00\\x00B\\x00\\x01default' > ws/default/image.png\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"default: modify png\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\nfile ws/feat/image.png\n# -> \"ASCII text\"   (was \"PNG image data\")\nxxd ws/feat/image.png | head -3\n# -> \"# structured conflict at image.png...\"\n```\n\n**Expected**: For binary files, either\n1. Write the workspace-side binary content verbatim and mark the file as conflicted via structured metadata only (never touch the binary bytes on disk).\n2. Leave the base version on disk and require the user to `--keep` before editing.\n3. At minimum, refuse to materialize text markers into a file git considers binary and print a clear \"binary conflict; use `maw ws resolve --keep <side>` to choose\" message.\n\n**Actual**: Binary content is silently overwritten with text. `--keep <side>` after does recover — so the bug is purely in the materialization step, not in the blobstore.\n\n**Impact**: High. Any workspace with a binary-file conflict is in a dangerous state until resolved. The corrupted on-disk file would be flagged as modified by git; a `maw exec feat -- git commit -am fix` from the agent would commit the text trash as the image. Downstream tools (thumbnail generators, asset pipelines, browsers) will fail or display garbage.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: The V1 structured render doesn't distinguish text vs binary. Either detect via first-512-byte NUL scan (same heuristic git uses) or via `.gitattributes` before writing diff3 markers.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"m","title":"Binary file conflicts overwrite working-tree with text placeholder on rebase"}	blake3:Zf-WXnqXHwBaRVf-JyA-4FPz8-zlsACxm40A9YhTCL4
1776730930547408	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyygs		item.create	bn-24tl	{"description":"**Issue**: When `conflict-tree.json` is corrupt/invalid JSON, `maw ws resolve --keep` falls back to the legacy text-marker path, which then hands the placeholder-markered file to a regex-based stripper. The stripper only removes the `=======` and `>>>>>>>` half of the markers, leaving the `<<<<<<<` half plus the garbage placeholder text in the file.\n\nOn a second `--keep` invocation the tool says \"skipped: s.txt — no conflict markers\" but the file is still clearly broken — the user is stuck with a file that looks half-resolved.\n\nAlso the output of a single `--keep` call is self-contradictory — it prints both \"resolved: s.txt\" and \"1 file(s) still have conflict markers.\" for the same file in the same run.\n\n**Reproduction**:\n\n```\n# Set up a conflicted rebase\necho base > ws/default/s.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\necho ws > ws/feat/s.txt && maw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m ws\necho epoch > ws/default/s.txt && maw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m epoch\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\n\n# Corrupt the structured tree so the fallback path triggers:\necho 'not valid json{{{' > .manifold/artifacts/ws/feat/conflict-tree.json\nmaw ws resolve feat --keep epoch\ncat ws/feat/s.txt\n```\n\n**Expected**: Either\n1. `--keep epoch` writes `epoch\\n` (full resolution).\n2. It loudly complains that structured metadata is missing/corrupt and refuses.\n\n**Actual**: File contents after `--keep epoch`:\n\n```\n# structured conflict at s.txt\n# base blob: df967b96a579e45a18b8251732d16804b2e56a55\n\n(epoch content not inlined in V1 structured render)\n```\n\nThe `=======` / `>>>>>>>` half was stripped; the `<<<<<<<` half stayed. Self-contradictory stdout in the same call: \"resolved: s.txt\" AND \"1 file(s) still have conflict markers.\" Subsequent `--keep epoch` calls report \"skipped: no conflict markers\" — the file is stuck in this garbage state with no user-friendly path out other than manually editing or re-running rebase.\n\n**Impact**: Medium. Normal users won't hit this, but corrupt/missing JSON artifacts can happen from a crashed rebase, aggressive gc, or disk full. Fallback should be either bulletproof or explicit.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: Fallback legacy resolver was written for real textual diff3 markers, not the V1 placeholder rendering used by the structured engine. The placeholder marker format is different enough that the half-stripper doesn't match the opening `<<<<<<< epoch (current)`. Two possible fixes: (a) make the placeholder rendering match the standard diff3 shape (linked to bn-324m), or (b) skip the legacy fallback when the markers are placeholder-shaped.\n\nRelated: bn-324m (placeholder content in structured render).","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"s","title":"Resolve fallback half-strips placeholder markers when conflict-tree.json is corrupt"}	blake3:q_X7S8BPucQnfmFvf_vwCyQvyeiZByIED7w04Ky1XN0
1776731005589609	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyyws		item.create	bn-2cc1	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws resolve <name> --keep <side>` says \"resolved\" and \"All structured conflicts resolved — workspace is ready for merge\" but the workspace is NOT actually ready for merge until the user runs `git add && git commit`. The subsequent `maw ws merge` then refuses with \"N unresolved conflict marker(s)\" because the gate inspects HEAD, not the working tree.\n\nThe instruction shown at the end of rebase does say to commit, but the `resolve` command's confirmation output directly contradicts that:\n\n```\nAll structured conflicts resolved — workspace is ready for merge.\n```\n\nFollowed by:\n\n```\n$ maw ws merge feat --into default --message \"x\"\nError: Workspace 'feat' has N unresolved conflict marker(s) in its worktree\n```\n\nA user who trusts the \"ready for merge\" message will bounce off this every time.\n\n**Reproduction**:\n\n```\n# Set up a conflicted rebase (use the scenario 23 setup with 3 files)\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\nmaw ws resolve feat --keep feat\nmaw ws merge feat --into default --message m    # errors\n```\n\n**Expected** (pick one):\n1. `resolve --keep` auto-stages and auto-commits the resolution (matches what `git rebase --continue` would do).\n2. The \"ready for merge\" line is changed to \"Run `maw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \\\"fix: resolve\\\"` to finalize.\"\n3. `maw ws merge` treats working-tree-clean-but-HEAD-has-markers as resolved if `conflict-tree.json` is marked resolved.\n\n**Actual**: Contradictory messaging, manual `git add && commit` required, merge gate looks at HEAD.\n\n**Impact**: Low-medium. UX paper cut; can waste minutes for a first-time user or an agent that trusts the tool's own \"ready for merge\" output.\n\n**Also**: `maw ws merge` attributes the conflict markers to the working tree (\"in its worktree\") but is actually detecting them in HEAD's tree. Message says \"worktree\" but checks committed state.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"s","title":"Resolve says 'ready for merge' but merge refuses until user manually git-commits"}	blake3:dM5yR5mv3rNp94CKH7ICktrEEpbdugz83wHFcswTGoo
1776731099132631	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyzAs		item.create	bn-3l5p	{"description":"**Issue**: Rebase errors out with an internal-looking message when the workspace and the epoch both add the same new path (classic add/add conflict). The error is cryptic and leaves the workspace in a \"stale\" state with no conflict-tree artifacts — no path forward shown to the user other than re-running sync or destroying the workspace.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\nmaw ws create feat --from main\necho WS_NEW > ws/feat/new.txt\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \"ws: new.txt\"\necho EPOCH_NEW > ws/default/new.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"default: new.txt\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\n```\n\n**Expected**:\n- The rebase should treat this as a normal conflict (it's the classic add/add scenario that git handles fine with `rebase --strategy=ort`).\n- The user should see a conflict with both sides preserved, same as any other rebase conflict. `maw ws resolve feat --keep feat` should write `WS_NEW` and `--keep epoch` should write `EPOCH_NEW`.\n\n**Actual**:\n\n```\nRebasing workspace 'feat' (1 commit(s)) onto epoch 24e992ff6893...\n\nError: apply_unilateral_patchset failed for 15e4a977990c: unexpected Added on conflicted path new.txt (existing shape: content)\n```\n\nAnd the workspace is now in a bad state:\n- `.manifold/artifacts/ws/feat/` does not exist (no conflict-tree.json, no rebase-conflicts.json)\n- `maw ws list` marks it as `(stale)` with no hint that the user should use `--rebase`\n- The error message mentions internal functions (`apply_unilateral_patchset`) and internal shape values (`existing shape: content`) — nothing actionable for the user\n\n**Impact**: High. Add/add is a real-world scenario (two agents independently add the same new file, or an agent adds a file that the lead also adds). Today this produces a hard error with no recovery path — the user has to either destroy the workspace (losing the commit) or manually hand-merge via raw git.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: The conflict-tree engine's shape-tracking classifies new.txt as a `content` conflict but the patch being applied is an `Added` patch. The mismatch triggers the guard. Fix is either (a) normalize add/add to a content conflict with base=empty, or (b) add explicit handling for add/add shape transitions.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup"],"size":"m","title":"Rebase crashes on add/add conflict with 'apply_unilateral_patchset failed'","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:5in16jFQyrPsmlc5FUXYUJ8Nqh8KoBhv_o_ujWCuC1U
1776731153906520	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyzQs		item.create	bn-2gex	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws resolve --help` advertises per-block resolution via `cf-N=NAME` and shows three separate examples using that syntax, but trying to use it errors out with \"Per-block `cf-N=NAME` keep-specs are not supported with the structured sidecar.\" Further: `--list` never prints the `cf-N` IDs either, so users can't even discover which `cf-N` to use.\n\nFrom the help text:\n\n```\n--keep accepts three forms:\n  NAME              resolve ALL conflicted files to NAME's version\n  PATH=NAME         resolve one file to NAME's version\n  cf-N=NAME         resolve one conflict block to NAME's version\n\nExamples:\n  maw ws resolve default --keep cf-0=bn-2sc3 --keep cf-1=default  # per-block\n  maw ws resolve default --keep cf-0=both --keep cf-1=bn-2sc3     # mix both + one side\n```\n\nFollowed by \"Use --list to see conflict blocks with their IDs\" — but `--list` output (both text and JSON) never includes cf-N IDs.\n\n**Reproduction**:\n\n```\n# Standard conflicted rebase setup\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\nmaw ws resolve feat --list                           # no cf-N shown\nmaw ws resolve feat --list s.txt                     # no cf-N shown\nmaw ws resolve feat --list --format json             # no cf-N in JSON\nmaw ws resolve feat --keep cf-0=feat                 # errors\n# Error: Per-block `cf-N=NAME` keep-specs are not supported with the structured sidecar.\n```\n\n**Expected**: Either\n1. Implement per-block and make `--list` show IDs.\n2. Remove `cf-N=NAME` from `--help` (and examples in --help output) until it's supported, add a \"Coming soon\" note if you want to keep users informed.\n\n**Actual**: Help text promises a feature that no path supports. The error message says \"tracked as a follow-up\" so the team knows — but that should mean the docs don't advertise it.\n\n**Impact**: Low (UX/honesty issue). Agents/users reading --help get misled. Breaks tab-complete scripting if someone automates from the help text.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial"],"size":"xs","title":"Resolve --help advertises cf-N=NAME per-block syntax that is not implemented"}	blake3:3hqnjIG996I_HVPNeCFG35YqkicTWe3KkowFf02Xiw0
