1776737582392838	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4Qs		item.create	bn-2pry	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws resolve <ws> --keep both` on a modify/delete conflict produces a file whose content is `<epoch-content>\\n<BASE-content>\\n`. The deleter side (`feat`, in the scenario below) has no content — the file was deleted — so `both` has nothing to append. Instead the tool appends the original base blob's bytes, labeling that implicitly as the \"feat side\". Users get silent data resurrection: content that was explicitly deleted by the workspace comes back under the banner \"keep both sides\".\n\nThe structured diagnostic (`resolve --list`) correctly labels this as `[modify_delete]`, so the engine knows it's a modify/delete — but the `both` resolution path doesn't branch on shape, it just concatenates both sides blindly, and for the deleted side it apparently falls back to the base blob.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\necho \"base\" > ws/default/dir/file.txt\nmkdir -p ws/default/dir\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\ncd ws/feat && git rm -r dir && git commit -m \"ws: remove dir\"\ncd -\necho \"epoch-mod\" > ws/default/dir/file.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"default: mod file\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat                 # produces modify/delete conflict\nmaw ws resolve feat --keep both\ncat ws/feat/dir/file.txt\n```\n\n**Expected** (pick one):\n1. For modify/delete, `--keep both` errors with \"shape `modify_delete` has no meaningful 'both' — pick `--keep <winner>` explicitly.\"\n2. `--keep both` is equivalent to `--keep <modifier>` for modify/delete (content survives, deletion ignored) and prints a note about the choice.\n3. `--keep both` concatenates epoch content plus an explicit comment line like `# NOTE: <ws-name> deleted this file`.\n\n**Actual**: File ends up with:\n```\nepoch-mod\nbase\n```\n\nThe word `base` here is the original base blob's content, which was wiped by both sides (epoch modified it, feat deleted the path). Neither side had `\"base\"` as its resolution content; reviving it makes no sense.\n\n**Impact**: Medium. Silent data resurrection of removed content under a banner (\"keep both\") that implies no data loss. If a user's `both` resolution is what they default to for safety (\"keep everything, sort it out later\"), they'll commit stale content they thought they'd deleted.\n\n**Root cause hypothesis**: `--keep both` implementation concatenates sides[0] and sides[1] without checking shape. For modify/delete one of those sides has no content stream, so the code falls back to the base blob's bytes instead of treating it as empty.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup","round2"],"size":"s","title":"Resolve --keep both on modify/delete conflict silently inlines base content as the 'deleter side'"}	blake3:c9sJZV7N3tJCHUhzcmg5GDSS7-WXtZerIheXYFso4S0
1776737681513422	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4gs		item.create	bn-mg0j	{"description":"**Issue**: When `maw ws sync --rebase` produces a conflict on a symlink (e.g. both epoch and workspace added a symlink with different targets, or both modified it to different targets), the conflict is materialized as a regular text file with diff3 markers — and after `maw ws resolve --keep <side>`, the file on disk remains a regular file (`100644`) containing the target-path bytes as its content. The `120000` symlink mode stored in the original commit is lost.\n\nThis is a distinct bug from bn-3gbi (closed), which covered non-conflicting symlinks during rebase. Here the issue is specifically the **conflict-materialize + resolve path** for symlinks.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\necho a > ws/default/a.txt\necho b > ws/default/b.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\n(cd ws/feat && ln -s a.txt link && git add link && git commit -m \"ws: link->a\")\n(cd ws/default && ln -s b.txt link && git add link && git commit -m \"default: link->b\")\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat                  # produces add/add conflict on `link`\nmaw ws resolve feat --keep feat\nls -la ws/feat/link                        # -rw-r--r-- regular file, not a symlink\ncat ws/feat/link                           # \"a.txt\"   (the target, now as content)\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m resolve\nmaw exec feat -- git ls-tree HEAD link     # \"100644 blob ... link\"  (not 120000)\n```\n\n**Expected**: After `--keep feat`, `ws/feat/link` is a symlink pointing at `a.txt`, git mode `120000`.\n\n**Actual**:\n- Conflict materialization writes a text file with diff3 markers at `ws/feat/link`. Even though both sides are symlinks, it's not obvious to the user the file used to be a symlink.\n- `--keep feat` writes the target-path (`a.txt`) as bytes to the regular file; it does NOT re-apply the symlink bit.\n- After `git add && git commit`, the tree permanently records `100644` for what used to be a `120000` symlink.\n\n**Impact**: Medium. Rare (symlink conflicts in practice are uncommon) but silent data corruption when it happens. A user resolving a symlink conflict ends up shipping a regular file with the target path hard-coded as bytes — identical symptom to bn-3gbi but via a different code path.\n\n**Expected fix**: During conflict materialization for symlinks, either\n1. Store the mode in the conflict-tree metadata and re-apply `120000` during `resolve --keep`.\n2. For symlink conflicts, refuse to materialize text markers and use metadata-only conflict (require `--keep` before the file exists on disk).\n\n**Related**: bn-3gbi (closed — non-conflict symlink path), bn-ad5z (binary file conflict materialization).","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","gjm8-followup","round2"],"size":"m","title":"Symlink conflict silently converts to regular file after rebase+resolve"}	blake3:Q9N6iagGuK86bioiNlXV04gzyRuOSRahXnb_LuteGXE
