1776739810726943	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy-As		item.create	bn-1i3t	{"description":"**Issue**: bn-3oau (closed) regressed. `maw ws merge` still uses a pure textual grep for `<<<<<<<` markers in worktree files and refuses to ship workspaces whose committed content legitimately contains conflict-marker strings (e.g. tutorials, docs, test fixtures). The rebase itself is clean (no sidecar at `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/conflict-tree.json`), so the gate has no structured reason to flag the file — it's purely guessing from raw byte content.\n\n**Reproduction** (fresh bootstrapped repo, maw 0.59.3):\n\n```\necho base > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\ncat > ws/feat/tutorial.md <<'MD'\n# Merge conflicts\n<<<<<<< mine\nmy version\n||||||| base\noriginal\n=======\ntheir version\n>>>>>>> theirs\nMD\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \"ws: tutorial\"\necho new > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m default\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat        # \"Replayed cleanly. Workspace 'feat' is now up to date.\"\nmaw ws merge feat --into default --message \"x\"\n```\n\n**Expected**: Merge proceeds. `tutorial.md` was not part of any conflict — no sidecar exists, rebase was clean. Gate should consult the structured conflict sidecar (or git index merge-stage entries), not raw byte grep.\n\n**Actual** (maw 0.59.3):\n```\nError: Workspace 'feat' has 1 unresolved conflict marker(s) in its worktree:\n  - tutorial.md\n  Resolve them first (strip <<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>> markers and commit), then retry.\n  To force merge anyway: maw ws merge feat --into default --force\n```\n\n`--force` bypasses the legitimate stale-counter safety (bn-3h90) so is not a clean workaround for this case.\n\n**Impact**: Blocks any workspace that adds docs/tests/fixtures containing diff3-marker strings. Reopen bn-3oau or new fix: gate should check sidecar or git index merge-stages, not `grep -r '<<<<<<<'`.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","round3","regression","gjm8-followup"],"size":"s","title":"Regression of bn-3oau: merge marker gate still false-positives on content with <<<<<<<  markers"}	blake3:RUx9QJCpv8fPJtdHVbuOROuCzwxDp0U3ZhZI9Jdo6KU
1776739891322648	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy-Qs		item.create	bn-2ras	{"description":"**Issue**: When a workspace contains a merge commit and is rebased onto an epoch that's advanced on an unrelated path, the replayed merge commit creates a \"phantom\" conflict on a file whose base, parent-0 and parent-1 versions are all byte-identical. Resolve is forced but has nothing to pick. Additionally the side names shown by `resolve --list` (e.g. `feat#merge-parent-0`) are not accepted by the usual `--keep feat` / `--keep epoch` helper text the CLI emits.\n\n**Reproduction** (fresh bootstrapped repo, maw 0.59.3):\n\n```\necho base > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\nEPOCH=$(maw exec feat -- git rev-parse HEAD)\n(cd ws/feat \\\n  && echo A1 > side1.txt && git add side1.txt && git commit -m \"A: side1\" \\\n  && git checkout -b sideB $EPOCH \\\n  && echo B1 > side2.txt && git add side2.txt && git commit -m \"B: side2\" \\\n  && git checkout - \\\n  && git merge --no-ff sideB -m \"merge sideB into A\" \\\n  && echo C > side1.txt && echo C > side2.txt && git add -A && git commit -m \"C: modify both\")\necho new > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"epoch advance\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\ncat ws/feat/side1.txt\n# -> `# structured conflict` marker where base=A1 parent-0=A1 parent-1=A1\nmaw ws resolve feat --list\n# side1.txt  [content] sides=[feat#merge-parent-0, feat#merge-parent-1]\n```\n\n**Expected**: No conflict produced — all three sides are byte-identical (\"A1\"). The replayed merge should trivially pick that content. C's subsequent \"side1.txt = C\" should land cleanly.\n\n**Actual**: Phantom conflict on side1.txt. Three-way content (\"A1\"/\"A1\"/\"A1\") is surfaced with diff3 markers. The side names are `feat#merge-parent-0` and `feat#merge-parent-1` — neither `--keep feat` nor `--keep epoch` (both suggested by the rebase output's help block) work; the user has to type `--keep feat#merge-parent-0` explicitly.\n\nSecondary issue: the post-rebase git log shows the left-parent's \"A: side1\" replayed AFTER \"B: side2\" (i.e. the merge parent topology is reordered), which is a correctness concern for `git log` consumers who expect chronological order.\n\n**Impact**: Medium. Any workspace with a merge commit that doesn't touch epoch-modified paths will spuriously conflict. Combined with the opaque side names, first-time users who ran the original bn-7mbe reproduction (which left HEAD clean) hit an unrelated conflict here. Lowest-effort fix: short-circuit identical-content three-way to no conflict. Also extend `--keep feat` as an alias for `feat#merge-parent-*` (or clearly document the convention).","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","round3","gjm8-followup"],"size":"m","title":"Rebase of merge commit emits phantom conflict when all 3 sides are byte-identical"}	blake3:0zHnbOgiFmVMfba0YGQsiNMptmj1Sfsh5e5FBCn67PU
