1776741903778674	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyggw		item.create	bn-m6ad	{"description":"**Regression of bn-1i3t and bn-3oau** (both marked `done`).\n\nRound 4 regression testing reproduced both bones verbatim with maw 0.59.3. The marker gate in `maw ws merge` still performs a pure textual grep for `<<<<<<<` on worktree files and blocks the merge even when the rebase was clean (no structured conflict sidecar) and the conflict-marker-like content is pre-existing legitimate file content (a tutorial, test fixture, etc).\n\n**Reproduction** (the exact repro from bn-1i3t / bn-3oau, maw 0.59.3):\n\n```\nTMP=$(mktemp -d -t maw-reg-XXXX); cd $TMP\ngit init -q && git commit -q --allow-empty -m initial\ngit config core.bare true\ngit worktree add -q ws/default\nmaw init\necho base > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\ncat > ws/feat/tutorial.md <<'MD'\n# Merge conflicts\n<<<<<<< mine\nmy version\n||||||| base\noriginal\n=======\ntheir version\n>>>>>>> theirs\nMD\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \"ws: tutorial\"\necho new > ws/default/noop.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m default\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat              # \"Replayed cleanly\"\nmaw ws merge feat --into default --message \"x\"\n```\n\n**Actual** (maw 0.59.3):\n```\nError: Workspace 'feat' has 1 unresolved conflict marker(s) in its worktree:\n  - tutorial.md\n  Resolve them first (strip <<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>> markers and commit), then retry.\n  To force merge anyway: maw ws merge feat --into default --force\n```\n\n**Expected** (from the closed bones): Merge proceeds because the rebase was clean — no sidecar at `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/conflict-tree.json`, no git index merge-stages. The gate should consult the structured sidecar or index stages, not raw byte grep.\n\n**Verification note**: The `conflict-tree.json` file does NOT exist at this point in the scenario (the workspace ran `sync --rebase` cleanly). So the gate has no structured reason to flag anything — it is purely grepping file content.\n\n**Impact**: Same as the original bones. Blocks any workspace that adds docs/tests/fixtures containing diff3-marker strings. `--force` bypasses the legitimate stale-counter safety. This is the third time the gate has been flagged on identical content.\n\n**Hypothesis**: The fix that closed bn-1i3t/bn-3oau may have been reverted, or only covered a subset of the trigger paths, or the gate-content-check was not actually changed (only the messaging was). Look for the textual check in the `ws merge` path — it still runs.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","round4","regression"],"size":"s","title":"Regression: marker gate still false-positives (bn-1i3t/bn-3oau regressed)"}	blake3:ghx6SVQ_Hw9EU845aIs8NK9iD0RRzrreqrID6HZB88g
1776741930932958	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEygww		item.create	bn-3pgl	{"description":"**Partial regression of bn-ad5z** (marked `done`).\n\nThe intermediate on-disk state of a binary file during conflict is still written as ASCII commentary, but the partial fix (adding a `# BINARY CONFLICT at ...` banner and trailing \"verbatim bytes\" block) has introduced a NEW failure mode: the merge gate does not see the corrupt text as a conflict marker (because the banner does not contain `<<<<<<<` at the expected offset in the way its grep expects), so a user who runs `maw ws merge` WITHOUT resolving ships the corrupt text as the final binary blob to default.\n\n**Reproduction** (maw 0.59.3):\n\n```\nTMP=$(mktemp -d -t maw-reg-XXXX); cd $TMP\ngit init -q && git commit -q --allow-empty -m initial\ngit config core.bare true\ngit worktree add -q ws/default\nmaw init\nprintf '\\x89PNG\\r\\n\\x1a\\n\\x00\\x00A\\x00\\x01base' > ws/default/image.png\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\nprintf '\\x89PNG\\r\\n\\x1a\\n\\x00\\x00A\\x00\\x01wsver' > ws/feat/image.png\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \"ws: modify png\"\nprintf '\\x89PNG\\r\\n\\x1a\\n\\x00\\x00B\\x00\\x01default' > ws/default/image.png\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"default: modify png\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\n# HEAD of feat now points at a commit whose tree stores text trash for image.png:\nmaw exec feat -- git show HEAD:image.png | head -c 80\n# -> \"# BINARY CONFLICT at image.png — inlined markers would corrupt the file...\"\n\n# User forgets to resolve, runs merge directly:\nmaw ws merge feat --into default --message \"merge\"\n# -> Succeeds silently. default now has text-trash in image.png.\nfile ws/default/image.png\n# -> \"ws/default/image.png: data\"  (looks like garbage, is garbage)\nxxd ws/default/image.png | head -1\n# -> \"00000000: 2320 4249 4e41 5259 2043 4f4e 464c 4943  # BINARY CONFLIC\"\n```\n\n**Expected** (improving on bn-ad5z's fix):\n1. Do NOT materialize the text commentary into the binary file at all; keep the workspace-side binary bytes on disk and record the conflict in structured metadata only. OR\n2. If materialized, the merge gate must refuse to merge any file whose index/tree matches the \"BINARY CONFLICT at\" banner, not just `<<<<<<<`.\n3. At minimum, `maw ws merge` should re-consult `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/conflict-tree.json` and refuse if any path is still listed there unresolved.\n\n**Actual**: Silent merge of text-trash as binary blob. The `--keep` recovery path still works if the user remembers — but the \"forget to resolve\" path now sails through the gate because the text banner does not contain `<<<<<<<` (it's `# BINARY CONFLICT at image.png -- inlined markers would corrupt the file.` followed by placeholder diff3 lines that DO contain `<<<<<<<`, which... should actually trigger the grep — let me double check).\n\nActually the generated text DOES contain `<<<<<<< epoch (current)` inside the banner, so the grep should fire. Yet `maw ws merge feat --into default` succeeds. Either the grep is not being run post-rebase-before-merge in this scenario, or it is silently skipped for binary-classified files. Either way, the end result is silent corruption.\n\n**Impact**: HIGH (data loss). Any workspace with a binary conflict that the user merges without resolve (easy mistake, especially for agents that run `sync --rebase` then `merge` in one pass) ships a text-trash blob claiming to be a binary file. Downstream build/asset pipelines will break.\n\n**Hypothesis**: Either (a) the marker gate is bypassed for files whose stored blob is classified \"binary\" (catch-22: the stored blob IS text because rebase wrote text), or (b) the gate only runs against the working tree and the working tree and HEAD agree (both text), so no markers to strip. Fix: gate on structured sidecar state, not marker textual grep.\n\n**Related**: bn-ad5z (original, closed), bn-m6ad (marker-gate regression filed same round).","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","round4","regression"],"size":"m","title":"Regression: binary conflict still committed as text trash (bn-ad5z partial regression)"}	blake3:5MyLdKtxaaHBA1ybsISfbHZ8BLFXFeSs7BiwyMMYt-4
1776741953503246	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyhAw		item.create	bn-3hqg	{"description":"**Issue**: `maw ws sync --rebase` fails with an internal-looking error when the workspace adds a git submodule. Submodules are gitlinks (mode 160000) pointing at a commit SHA in another repository; the maw rebase engine treats that SHA as a blob and tries to fetch it, which fails because it does not exist as a blob.\n\n**Reproduction** (maw 0.59.3):\n\n```\nTMP=$(mktemp -d -t maw-sub-XXXX); cd $TMP\ngit init -q && git commit -q --allow-empty -m initial\ngit config core.bare true\ngit worktree add -q ws/default\nmaw init\n\n# Create a small repo to use as the submodule:\nSUBREPO=$(mktemp -d -t maw-subrepo-XXXX)\n(cd $SUBREPO && git init -q && echo sub > sub.txt && git add -A && git commit -qm \"sub init\")\n\necho base > ws/default/f.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\n(cd ws/feat && git -c protocol.file.allow=always submodule add $SUBREPO subdir && git commit -m \"ws: add submodule\")\necho changed > ws/default/f.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m \"epoch change\"\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws sync --rebase feat\n```\n\n**Expected** (pick one):\n1. The rebase correctly replays the gitlink (160000 mode pointing at the submodule's HEAD SHA).\n2. The rebase refuses with a clear \"submodules not supported yet\" message and leaves the workspace unchanged.\n3. The rebase warns and drops the submodule gracefully.\n\n**Actual**:\n```\nRebasing workspace 'feat' (1 commit(s)) onto epoch 4f2b465231bf...\n\nError: Failed to extract patchset for 69226c966657: git repo error: not found: blob e190ec8f87f55e85dee637b76335845be7b200da: An object with id e190ec8f87f55e85dee637b76335845be7b200da could not be found\n```\n\nThe error exposes internal function names and treats the submodule's commit SHA as a blob. The workspace is left in a state where `ws/feat/subdir/` exists empty (no submodule checkout), the rebase failed partway through, and there is no clear recovery.\n\n**Impact**: Low for most users (submodules are rare) but high for anyone with a monorepo-with-submodules workflow. The error message mentions internal implementation details (`Failed to extract patchset`) that are useless to an end user.\n\n**Hypothesis**: The patchset-extraction code walks tree entries and, for each entry, fetches the blob it points at. Gitlink entries (mode 160000) point at commit objects, not blobs, so the fetch fails. Fix is to either skip gitlink entries during patchset computation, or handle them as a distinct entry type.\n\n**Workaround**: None. User must `maw ws destroy feat` and redo without the submodule.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","round4"],"size":"m","title":"Rebase fails with internal 'not found: blob' error when workspace has a submodule"}	blake3:gXCppVSWKQbC3KTgSuV8DV_VIxLVb8UEDO-pRGcXDcY
1776741971063282	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyhQw		item.create	bn-1d1g	{"description":"**Issue**: Running two `maw ws sync --rebase <name>` processes concurrently on the same workspace races. One process wins, the other fails partway through with an internal-looking error (`set_head failed: ... No such file or directory`), and the workspace is left with the \"loser\" process's partial state — in the test case, 20 files marked as conflicted even though a single-process rebase on the same setup produces 0 conflicts in some paths (because the same commits are re-replayed against an intermediate HEAD).\n\n**Reproduction** (maw 0.59.3):\n\n```\nTMP=$(mktemp -d -t maw-conc-XXXX); cd $TMP\ngit init -q && git commit -q --allow-empty -m initial\ngit config core.bare true\ngit worktree add -q ws/default\nmaw init\n\n# Big enough to race: 20 files, 20 commits\nfor i in $(seq 1 20); do echo \"base $i\" > ws/default/f$i.txt; done\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\nfor i in $(seq 1 20); do\n  echo \"ws $i\" > ws/feat/f$i.txt\n  maw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m \"ws: $i\"\ndone\nfor i in $(seq 1 20); do echo \"epoch $i\" > ws/default/f$i.txt; done\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m epoch\nmaw epoch sync\n\n# Race two rebases:\n(maw ws sync --rebase feat > /tmp/a.log 2>&1) &\n(maw ws sync --rebase feat > /tmp/b.log 2>&1) &\nwait\n```\n\nOne process emits:\n```\nError: set_head failed: git backend error: failed to rename temp HEAD into place at /tmp/.../repo.git/worktrees/feat/HEAD: No such file or directory (os error 2)\n```\n\n**Expected** (pick one):\n1. File-lock the workspace at the start of `ws sync --rebase` (acquire `.manifold/artifacts/ws/<name>/rebase.lock` or flock the workspace's HEAD) and have the second process wait or exit with a clear \"another rebase is in progress\" message.\n2. Detect the race at the end and either retry or print a clear user-facing message with instructions.\n\n**Actual**: Internal error with OS-level path in the message; no guidance. The workspace ends in a state that depends on which process wins, which is non-deterministic.\n\n**Impact**: Low (concurrent rebase is an unusual user operation) but increases with multi-agent workflows where two agents may each decide to sync a shared workspace. The error is opaque and leaves the workspace potentially with stale conflict artifacts from the loser's partial work.\n\n**Hypothesis**: No workspace-level lock file or advisory lock is taken during rebase. The underlying `gix` operation atomically renames a temp HEAD file, but process A can rename after process B has already renamed, leaving A's temp file pointing at a path that no longer exists as expected.\n\n**Workaround**: Users must not run concurrent rebases. No lock file is documented.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","round4"],"size":"s","title":"Concurrent 'ws sync --rebase' on same workspace races to clobber HEAD with internal error"}	blake3:uBjgZG0Kik75Jy82HM23gGoesg9knRF44gr1Cd1wh8c
