1776795792890030	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylgw		item.create	bn-28d1	{"description":"**Issue**: After a `sync --rebase` conflict, the sidecar (`conflict-tree.json`) contains `{\"clean\": {}, \"conflicts\": { PATH: {...} }, \"base_epoch\": ...}`. If the `conflicts` map is emptied (e.g. overwritten to `{\"clean\": {}, \"conflicts\": {}, \"base_epoch\": ...}`) while the working-tree files *still* contain the structured conflict-marker text, `maw ws merge` proceeds with no warning and commits the conflict-markered blob into the default branch. This produces a \"clean\" epoch advance whose tree has `<<<<<<< epoch (current) ... >>>>>>> feat` text in a real source file.\n\nThe sidecar-authoritative gate (bn-m6ad / bn-3pgl) is sidecar-only: it does not cross-check the workspace HEAD commit for leftover placeholder bytes (e.g. the distinctive `# structured conflict at PATH` header or the `(epoch content not inlined...)` binary placeholder). A tampered or truncated sidecar (corruption, race during write, malicious edit, partial disk-full) turns the gate off completely.\n\n**Reproduction** (from a fresh bootstrapped repo):\n\n```\nTMP=$(mktemp -d) && cd $TMP\ngit init -q && git commit -q --allow-empty -m init\ngit config core.bare true && git worktree add -q ws/default\nmaw init >/dev/null\n\necho base > ws/default/f.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m base\nmaw epoch sync\nmaw ws create feat --from main\n\necho ws > ws/feat/f.txt\nmaw exec feat -- git add -A && maw exec feat -- git commit -m ws\necho epoch > ws/default/f.txt\nmaw exec default -- git add -A && maw exec default -- git commit -m epoch\nmaw epoch sync\n\nmaw ws sync feat --rebase         # conflict on f.txt, sidecar written\n\n# Tamper: empty the conflicts map but leave on-disk markers alone\nSIDECAR=$(find . -name conflict-tree.json | head -1)\npython3 -c \"import json; d=json.load(open('$SIDECAR')); d['conflicts']={}; json.dump(d, open('$SIDECAR','w'))\"\n\n# Merge now succeeds — and commits the markered file.\nmaw ws merge feat --into default --message tampered\ncat ws/default/f.txt\n# -> prints the entire \"<<<<<<< epoch (current) ... >>>>>>> feat\" block\ngit -C ws/default show HEAD:f.txt     # the markered text is in the tree\n```\n\n**Expected**: At least one of\n1. Merge cross-checks the workspace HEAD tree for the distinctive `# structured conflict at ` header (or the `# BINARY CONFLIC` binary placeholder) and refuses if found, independent of the sidecar.\n2. `conflict-tree.json` is signed / checksummed / tied to a specific workspace HEAD sha so tampering/truncation is detectable.\n3. After rebase the workspace is left on a ref such that the markered blobs cannot be committed until `resolve` rewrites them.\n\n**Actual**: The tampered sidecar makes the gate say \"no conflicts\", merge proceeds, and the default branch ends up with conflict-marker text baked into a real source file.\n\n**Impact**: High-severity corruption vector. Not just a malicious case — any situation where the sidecar gets emptied/truncated (partial write crash, buggy tool, cleanup script that thinks the sidecar is stale) silently flips safety off. The round-4 fix (bn-m6ad/bn-3pgl) moved trust from marker-scan to sidecar; this shows the sidecar is now the *only* trust anchor with nothing to cross-check it.\n\n**Hypothesis for fix**: Keep the sidecar as the primary truth, but add a cheap \"tripwire\" — e.g. refuse to merge if any file in the workspace HEAD tree starts with the exact byte sequence `# structured conflict at ` or `# BINARY CONFLICT at `. Those strings are tool-authored and would only appear if a rebase-materialized placeholder was committed, which is always a bug / corruption.","kind":"bug","labels":["adversarial","round5","regression"],"size":"m","title":"Tampered sidecar (empty conflicts map) lets conflict-markered text merge into default","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:JmReVGmZT8A1nk6NAhVP41sa7QG3i7fOK8JGYT7_E_U
1776795816615016	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylww		item.comment	bn-28d1	{"body":"Additional repro: deleting BOTH sidecars (conflict-tree.json AND rebase-conflicts.json) has the same effect as tampering — merge proceeds and commits markered text. So the trust surface is \"at least one sidecar present and non-empty\", and the sidecar dir is a non-ref-tracked .manifold/artifacts/ws/<ws>/ directory that users and cleanup scripts could easily blow away without realizing. Suggests the fix should lean more heavily on workspace-HEAD content inspection (looking for tool-authored placeholder headers) rather than only trusting the sidecar."}	blake3:qTphQQul66em5ISQsearSCsh6jcXtd7wE10HnmPacoo
